{"title_page": "Coldharbour Lane", "text_new": "{{for|the 1982 song by Tom Robinson|Coldharbour Lane (song)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2015}}\n[[File:Coldharbour Lane April 2007.jpg|right|thumb|Coldharbour Lane seen from [[Acre Lane]].]]\n'''Coldharbour Lane''' is a road in [[south London]] that leads south-westwards from [[Camberwell]] to [[Brixton]]. The road is over {{convert|1|mile}} long with a mixture of residential, business and retail buildings - the stretch of Coldharbour Lane near [[Brixton Market]] contains shops, bars and restaurants. Between the junctions of Coldharbour Lane and [[Denmark Hill]] in [[Camberwell]] [[SE postcode area|SE5]] and Coldharbour Lane and Denmark Road lies part of the boundary between [[London Borough of Lambeth|Lambeth]] and [[London Borough of Southwark|Southwark]] boroughs. The other end of Coldharbour Lane meets [[Acre Lane]] in central Brixton to form the [[A2217 road|A2217]].\n\nThe [[Loughborough Junction]] area, surrounding the [[Loughborough Junction railway station|railway station]], marks the approximate centre point of Coldharbour Lane and the change in postcode from SE5 to [[SW postcode area|SW9]].\n\n==History==\nColdharbour Lane was formerly known as '''Camberwell Lane'''.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nFormer British Prime Minister [[John Major]] lived in a flat at 144 Coldharbour Lane when a child from 1955-59.<ref>{{cite book|author=John Major|title=John Major: The Autobiography|publisher=Harper Collins|year=1999|page=16-7}}</ref>\n\nThe lane close by Brixton Market became very derelict by the mid-1960s, when many drug houses flourished dealing mainly in cannabis.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 1981 the [[1981 Brixton riot|Brixton riots]] occurred in roads near Coldharbour Lane and some windows were broken on the street itself.<ref>[http://www.urban75.org/brixton/history/riot.html \"Brixton Riots, 10-12th April 1981\"], an eye-witness accounts of the Brixton disorders in and around the Frontline, Atlantic Road, [[Railton Road]], Coldharbour Lane and Brixton Road, Brixton, Lambeth, London.<!-- Bot generated title --></ref> With the support of community leaders and shop owners, there are plans to set up a mini-police station on Coldharbour Lane in the former premises of a drug dealer.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/britain/article/0,,1468736,00.html | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Ghetto fabulous | date=2005-04-24 | accessdate=2010-04-30}}</ref>{{update after|2017|9|27}}\n\n=== Origins of the name ===\nA possible derivation of the name is Cool Arbour Lane, dating from the time Camberwell was in the country. This is cited in 'The Streets' by Anthony Quinn (2012) as the place the [[Nymphalis antiopa|Camberwell beauty]] was first sighted.\n\nA \"cold harbour\" was an uninhabited shelter for travellers, often along a well-known route, somewhat similar to a modern [[bothy]]. Unlike an inn, there were no staff, food or drink to be had. There would be a roof, door and possibly a simple hearth, although it was the traveller's responsibility to gather fuel. They were generally little more than open-faced barns or animal shelters.<ref name=\"Phrases, Coldharbour\" >{{cite web\n |title=Coldharbour \n |url=http://www.phrases.org.uk/bulletin_board/43/messages/866.html\n |publisher=The Phrase Finder\n}}</ref>\n\nJ. C. Hahn, in ''[[Notes and Queries]]'' Series 3, 7, 253\u2013254 (1 April 1865) and later in Series 3, 8, 71\u201372 (22 July 1865) wrote an article entitled \"Remarks on the Origin of 'Cold Harbour'\".<ref>[http://www.cantab.net/users/michael.behrend/repubs/karslake/pages/hahn.html J. C. Hahn, Two articles on the origin of the name Coldharbour.]</ref>\n\nIn this, the author remarks upon relatively early equivalent place names in Germany and traces back the origins of Coldharbour/Cold Harbour to the Old High German Kalte Herberge. There is a village in [[Germany]] and another in [[Austria]] called Kaltherberg. This etymology was accepted by the authors of the dictionary [[Merriam-Webster]]. Our author concludes that \"our Cold Harbour was a name given to any cold abode, cold retreat, brought over to England by our Saxon ancestors\u2014Cold Harbour = Cold Station, Cold House, Cold Lodge.\" And thus has a wider meaning than that attributed by the supporters of a basic type of lodgings.\n\n\"Coldharbour\" also survives as the name of [[Coldharbour, Surrey|a village]] in [[Surrey]], and [[Bristol]] has both a \"Coldharbour Road\" and a \"Cold Harbour Lane\".\n\nColdharbour Lane also gives its name to [[Coldharbour (Lambeth ward)|Coldharbour ward]] in [[Brixton]] although approximately one third of Coldharbour Lane is located in [[Herne Hill ward]].\n\n== Crime == \nIn a 2003 London Evening Standard journalist David Cohen described Coldharbour Lane as the most dangerous street in the most dangerous borough in London. The headline asked whether the street is 'the most dangerous in Britain'. <ref>Evening Standard, 30/01/2003 Page: 16 Nearly 15,000 stabbings, robberies, muggings and even murders ... most linked to 300 yards where \u00a31m of crack cocaine is dealt each month. Is this the most dangerous street in Britain? INVESTIGATION: The Standard spends 24 hours in the London borough where the police fight their biggest battle against crime By: DAVID COHEN </ref>\n\nIn 1997, the street was the scene of several shootings. Devon Dawson, a 29-year-old Jamaican in the UK with a six month visa, was shot dead with a sub-machine gun outside the Green Man pub on Coldharbour Lane in April 1997.<ref>Evening Standard, 27/05/1997 Dealing out death on the streets People used to fight with fists or knives, now they go for a gun'  By: JUSTIN DAVENPORT </ref>On 3 June 1997 Anthony Baker was shot in the head during a raid at the Control Tower takeaway in Coldharbour Lane, Brixton, where he worked. The shooting happened just a few hundred yards from Lambeth Town Hall where, at the same time, Chief Inspector Alan O'Gorman was telling a packed meeting that gun crime in the area was becoming out of control. <ref>Evening Standard, 07/07/1997 Edition: A Page: 20 FORMER GANGSTER JOINS FIGHT TO END BRIXTON GUN WARSBy: MARC WADSWORTH </ref>\n\nThree graffiti artists died when they were hit by a train at Loughborough Junction station on Coldharbour Lane in June 2018. The three men's deaths sparked controversy after a former Transport for London (TfL) board member Brian Cooke described the dead men as \"common scum who cost the railway millions and keep fares high\".<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-44534102</ref>\n\n== 2014 Council Election ==\n\n===Coldharbour===\n{{Election box begin | title=Coldharbour (3)}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Rachel Heywood *\n  |votes      = 2,232\n  |percentage = 57.8\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Matt Parr *\n  |votes      = 2,037\n  |percentage = \n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Donatus Anyanwu *\n  |votes      = 2,014\n  |percentage =\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Green Party of England and Wales\n  |candidate  = Solomon Smith \n  |votes      = 742\n  |percentage = 19.2\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Green_Party_of_England_and_Wales\n  |candidate  = Thomas Wood\n  |votes      = 680\n  |percentage =\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Green_Party_of_England_and_Wales\n  |candidate  = Rashid Nix\n  |votes      = 638\n  |percentage =\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Yvonne Stewart-Williams \n  |votes      = 398\n  |percentage = 6.0\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n  |candidate  = Rachel Lester\n  |votes      = 225\n  |percentage = 5.8\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Carl Belgrove\n  |votes      = 224\n  |percentage =\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Edward Watkins\n  |votes      = 221\n  |percentage =\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = UK Independence Party\n  |candidate  = Johan Ward\n  |votes      = 127\n  |percentage = 3.3\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n  |candidate  = Michael Morfey\n  |votes      = 126\n  |percentage =\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link |\n  |party      = Liberal Democrats (UK) \n  |candidate  = Simon Waddington\n  |votes      = 126\n  |percentage =\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link |\n  |party      = Independent politician \n  |candidate  = David Warner\n  |votes      = 100\n  |percentage = 2.6\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link |\n  |party      = Independent politician \n |candidate  = Boniface Awogta\n  |votes      = 76\n  |percentage = 2.0\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box total|\n  |votes      = \n  |percentage =\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n |winner = Labour Party (UK)\n |loser = \n |swing  = \n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n |winner = Labour Party (UK) \n |loser = \n |swing  = \n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n |winner = Labour Party (UK)\n |swing  = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n- Rachel Heywood was elected as a Labour Councillor. Heywood resigned the party whip in April 2016 and now sits as an Independent councillor.<ref>https://moderngov.lambeth.gov.uk/mgMemberIndex.aspx?bcr=1</ref><ref>http://www.brixtonbuzz.com/2016/04/cllr-rachel-heywood-delivers-stinging-attack-on-labour-cabinet-elite-with-a-call-for-change-of-direction/</ref><ref>https://moderngov.lambeth.gov.uk/mgElectionAreaResults.aspx?XXR=0&ID=113&RPID=29273364</ref>\n\n==Pubs and bars==\nThere are several pubs and bars on Coldharbour Lane: the Prince of Wales in Brixton <ref>[http://www.beerintheevening.com/pubs/s/34/345/Prince_of_Wales/Brixton Prince of Wales, Brixton, London, SW9 8HH - pub details # beerintheevening.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> which has been on the same site since 1800;<ref>[http://www.urban75.org/brixton/history/prince.html Prince of Wales hotel, Coldharbour Lane, Brixton. Historical Brixton - old and new photos of Brixton, Lambeth, London, SW9 and SW2<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> the Prince Albert<ref>[http://fancyapint.com/pubs/pub1571.html The Prince Albert, 418 Coldharbour Lane, Brixton SW9 8LF<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> which has occasional live music and quiz nights;<ref>[http://www.allinlondon.co.uk/clubs_bars/venue-2312.php Prince Albert, 418 Coldharbour Lane, London - London Public Houses & Inns - All in London<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> the Dogstar,<ref>[http://www.beerintheevening.com/pubs/s/31/317/Dogstar/Brixton Dogstar, Brixton, London, SW9 8LQ - pub details # beerintheevening.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> a \"three-floor DJ bar\";<ref>[http://fancyapint.com/pubs/pub3152.html Dogstar, 389 Coldharbour Lane, Brixton SW9 8LQ<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Living;<ref>[http://www.mybrixton.com/brixton/bars&Music-reviews-living.htm Living | 443 Coldharbour Lane | London | SW9 8LN<!-- Bot generated title -->{{dead link|date=February 2015}}]</ref> Club 414<ref>[http://www.mybrixton.com/brixton/bars&Music-reviews-club-414.htm Club 414 | 414 Coldharbour Lane | London | SW9 8LF<!-- Bot generated title -->{{dead link|date=February 2015}}]</ref>, The Sun<ref>https://web.archive.org/save/https://suncamberwell.com/</ref>, The Junction jazz club<ref>https://web.archive.org/save/http://thejunction.london/about-us-2/</ref> and the Plough. The Green Man,<ref>[http://www.mybrixton.com/brixton/bars&Music-review-the_green_man.htm The Green Man | 225 Coldharbour Lane | London | SW9 8RR<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> the Angel,<ref>[http://www.mybrixton.com/brixton/bars&Music-reviews-angel.htm The Angel | 354 Coldharbour Lane | London | SW9 8QH<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> the Enterprise and the Hero (alatterly the Junction) all ceased trading between 2000 and 2007 .\n\n==Mentions in culture==\nWith a nod to [[The Rolling Stones]]' ''[[Exile on Main St.]]'', Brixton-based band [[Alabama 3]] named their debut album ''[[Exile on Coldharbour Lane]]'' after the road. Although \"[[Woke Up This Morning]]\" on this album mentions Coldharbour Lane, the mention is omitted from the \"Chosen One Mix\", used as the theme song for ''[[The Sopranos]]''.\n\n\"Coldharbour Lane\" &mdash; with the hook \"So long / I've done my time / Coldharbour Lane / Goodbye\" &mdash; is a single from [[The Quireboys]]'s 2001 ''[[This Is Rock'n'Roll]]'' release.\n\n[[Markus Schulz]] named his own recording label \"Coldharbour Recordings\" in honour of the time when he lived in a flat in Coldharbour Lane.\n\nThe area features in the 2008 novel by [[Stella Duffy]] The Room Of Lost Things, set in a dry cleaners on Coldharbour Lane.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/feb/21/room-of-lost-things-review</ref>\n\n[[Oladipo Agboluaje]] set a play referencing the street in 2007 \"The Christ of Coldharbour Lane\", about the sudden reappearance of Jesus Christ in Brixton. <ref>https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2007/jun/08/theatre1</ref>\n\nParts of [[Honeytrap]], a 2015 film directed by Rebecca Johnson and starring [[Jessica Sula]], were filmed on the street.\n<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/may/07/honeytrap-review-jessica-sula</ref>\n\n==The Camberwell beauty==\n[[File:Nymphalis antiopa.JPG|thumb|right|Camberwell beauty butterfly]]\nThe rare migrant butterfly, the [[Camberwell beauty]] (''Nymphalis antiopa'') was so named after the discovery of two specimens in Coldharbour Lane in 1748.<ref name=Asher>Asher, Jim. ''The Atlas of Butterflies of Britain and Ireland'', Oxford University Press.</ref><ref name=Thomas>Thomas, Jeremy, and Richard Lewington. ''The Butterflies of Britain and Ireland'', Dorling Kindersley.</ref> The butterflies had probably arrived as stowaways on ships delivering timber from Scandinavia to the Surrey Docks two miles to the north.<ref name=Emmet>Emmet, A. M. and Heath, J. (1989). ''The Moths and Butterflies of Great Britain and Ireland'', Harley Books, Colchester.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{coord|51.4659|-0.1024|type:landmark_region:GB-LBH|display=title}} <!-- approximate midpoint -->\n\n[[Category:Streets in the London Borough of Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Streets in the London Borough of Southwark]]\n[[Category:Camberwell]]\n[[Category:Brixton]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the 1982 song by Tom Robinson|Coldharbour Lane (song)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2015}}\n[[File:Coldharbour Lane April 2007.jpg|right|thumb|Coldharbour Lane seen from [[Acre Lane]].]]\n'''Coldharbour Lane''' is a road in [[south London]] that leads south-westwards from [[Camberwell]] to [[Brixton]]. The road is over {{convert|1|mile}} long with a mixture of residential, business and retail buildings - the stretch of Coldharbour Lane near [[Brixton Market]] contains shops, bars and restaurants. Between the junctions of Coldharbour Lane and [[Denmark Hill]] in [[Camberwell]] [[SE postcode area|SE5]] and Coldharbour Lane and Denmark Road lies part of the boundary between [[London Borough of Lambeth|Lambeth]] and [[London Borough of Southwark|Southwark]] boroughs. The other end of Coldharbour Lane meets [[Acre Lane]] in central Brixton to form the [[A2217 road|A2217]].\n\nThe [[Loughborough Junction]] area, surrounding the [[Loughborough Junction railway station|railway station]], marks the approximate centre point of Coldharbour Lane and the change in postcode from SE5 to [[SW postcode area|SW9]].\n\n==History==\nColdharbour Lane was formerly known as '''Camberwell Lane'''.\n\nFormer British Prime Minister [[John Major]] lived in a flat at 144 Coldharbour Lane when a child from 1955-59.<ref>{{cite book|author=John Major|title=John Major: The Autobiography|publisher=Harper Collins|year=1999|page=16-7}}</ref>\n\nThe lane close by Brixton Market became very derelict by the mid-1960s, when many drug houses flourished dealing mainly in cannabis.\n\nIn 1981 the [[1981 Brixton riot|Brixton riots]] occurred in roads near Coldharbour Lane and some windows were broken on the street itself.<ref>[http://www.urban75.org/brixton/history/riot.html \"Brixton Riots, 10-12th April 1981\"], an eye-witness accounts of the Brixton disorders in and around the Frontline, Atlantic Road, [[Railton Road]], Coldharbour Lane and Brixton Road, Brixton, Lambeth, London.<!-- Bot generated title --></ref> With the support of community leaders and shop owners, there are plans to set up a mini-police station on Coldharbour Lane in the former premises of a drug dealer.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/britain/article/0,,1468736,00.html | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Ghetto fabulous | date=2005-04-24 | accessdate=2010-04-30}}</ref>{{update after|2017|9|27}}\n\n=== Origins of the name ===\nA possible derivation of the name is Cool Arbour Lane, dating from the time Camberwell was in the country. This is cited in 'The Streets' by Anthony Quinn (2012) as the place the [[Nymphalis antiopa|Camberwell beauty]] was first sighted.\n\nA \"cold harbour\" was an uninhabited shelter for travellers, often along a well-known route, somewhat similar to a modern [[bothy]]. Unlike an inn, there were no staff, food or drink to be had. There would be a roof, door and possibly a simple hearth, although it was the traveller's responsibility to gather fuel. They were generally little more than open-faced barns or animal shelters.<ref name=\"Phrases, Coldharbour\" >{{cite web\n |title=Coldharbour \n |url=http://www.phrases.org.uk/bulletin_board/43/messages/866.html\n |publisher=The Phrase Finder\n}}</ref>\n\nJ. C. Hahn, in ''[[Notes and Queries]]'' Series 3, 7, 253\u2013254 (1 April 1865) and later in Series 3, 8, 71\u201372 (22 July 1865) wrote an article entitled \"Remarks on the Origin of 'Cold Harbour'\".<ref>[http://www.cantab.net/users/michael.behrend/repubs/karslake/pages/hahn.html J. C. Hahn, Two articles on the origin of the name Coldharbour.]</ref>\n\nIn this, the author remarks upon relatively early equivalent place names in Germany and traces back the origins of Coldharbour/Cold Harbour to the Old High German Kalte Herberge. There is a village in [[Germany]] and another in [[Austria]] called Kaltherberg. This etymology was accepted by the authors of the dictionary [[Merriam-Webster]]. Our author concludes that \"our Cold Harbour was a name given to any cold abode, cold retreat, brought over to England by our Saxon ancestors\u2014Cold Harbour = Cold Station, Cold House, Cold Lodge.\" And thus has a wider meaning than that attributed by the supporters of a basic type of lodgings.\n\n\"Coldharbour\" also survives as the name of [[Coldharbour, Surrey|a village]] in [[Surrey]], and [[Bristol]] has both a \"Coldharbour Road\" and a \"Cold Harbour Lane\".\n\nColdharbour Lane also gives its name to [[Coldharbour (Lambeth ward)|Coldharbour ward]] in [[Brixton]] although approximately one third of Coldharbour Lane is located in [[Herne Hill ward]].\n\n== Crime == \nIn a 2003 London Evening Standard journalist David Cohen described Coldharbour Lane as the most dangerous street in the most dangerous borough in London. The headline asked whether the street is 'the most dangerous in Britain'. <ref>Evening Standard, 30/01/2003 Page: 16 Nearly 15,000 stabbings, robberies, muggings and even murders ... most linked to 300 yards where \u00a31m of crack cocaine is dealt each month. Is this the most dangerous street in Britain? INVESTIGATION: The Standard spends 24 hours in the London borough where the police fight their biggest battle against crime By: DAVID COHEN </ref>\n\nIn 1997, the street was the scene of several shootings. Devon Dawson, a 29-year-old Jamaican in the UK with a six month visa, was shot dead with a sub-machine gun outside the Green Man pub on Coldharbour Lane in April 1997.<ref>Evening Standard, 27/05/1997 Dealing out death on the streets People used to fight with fists or knives, now they go for a gun'  By: JUSTIN DAVENPORT </ref>On 3 June 1997 Anthony Baker was shot in the head during a raid at the Control Tower takeaway in Coldharbour Lane, Brixton, where he worked. The shooting happened just a few hundred yards from Lambeth Town Hall where, at the same time, Chief Inspector Alan O'Gorman was telling a packed meeting that gun crime in the area was becoming out of control. <ref>Evening Standard, 07/07/1997 Edition: A Page: 20 FORMER GANGSTER JOINS FIGHT TO END BRIXTON GUN WARSBy: MARC WADSWORTH </ref>\n\nThree graffiti artists died when they were hit by a train at Loughborough Junction station on Coldharbour Lane in June 2018. The three men's deaths sparked controversy after a former Transport for London (TfL) board member Brian Cooke described the dead men as \"common scum who cost the railway millions and keep fares high\".<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-44534102</ref>\n\n== 2014 Council Election ==\n\n===Coldharbour===\n{{Election box begin | title=Coldharbour (3)}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Rachel Heywood *\n  |votes      = 2,232\n  |percentage = 57.8\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Matt Parr *\n  |votes      = 2,037\n  |percentage = \n  |change     =\n