&pg=PA87#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=Centennial History of the City of Washington, D.C. |publisher=United Brethren Publishing House |place=Dayton, Ohio |title=IV. \"Permanent Capital Site Selected\"|page=87|lccn=06028029|oclc=2843595 |accessdate=2009-05-07|via=[[Google Books]]}}\n*{{cite book|last=Graham|first=Shirley|author-link=Shirley Graham Du Bois|year=1949|url=https://archive.org/details/yourmosthumblese00dubo/page/n8/mode/1up|title=Your Most Humble Servant|lccn=49011346|oclc=1036934508|accessdate=April 15, 2020|location=New York|publisher=[[Julian Messner|Julian Messner, Inc.]]|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book|last=Jusserand|first=Jean Jules|author-link=Jean Jules Jusserand |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u2MUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA137#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=With Americans of Past and Present Days||oclc=1075914 |title=Major L'Enfant and the Federal City |location=New York |publisher=[[Charles Scribner's Sons]] |pages=137\u2013195 |year=1916 |accessdate=2011-08-15 |via=[[Google Books]]}}\n* {{cite book|last=Latrobe|first=John H. B., Esq.|url=https://archive.org/details/memoirbenjaminb00socigoog/page/n7/mode/1up|title=Memoir of Benjamin Banneker: Read before the Maryland Historical Society at the Monthly Meeting, May 1, 1845|location=Baltimore, Maryland|publisher=Printed by John D. Toy|year=1845|lccn=rc01003345|oclc=85791076|accessdate=February 29, 2020|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book|last=Morrison|first=Hugh Alexander|url=https://archive.org/details/preliminarycheck00morr|title=Preliminary Check List of American Almanacs: 1639-1800|work=Library of Congress|year=1907|publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office|Government Printing Office]]|oclc=577096527|lccn=06035021|location=Washington, D.C.|accessdate=December 31, 2018|via=[[Internet Archive]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231033020/https://books.google.com/books?id=7JRJ-AXbTTMC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0|archive-date=December 31, 2018}}\n* {{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/DKC0021/mode/1up|title=A plan of a Peace-Office for the United States|work=Essays, Literary, Moral and Philosophical.|last=Rush|first=Benjamin, M.D.|author-link=Benjamin Rush|year=1798|place=Philadelphia |publisher=Thomas and William Bradford |accessdate=2019-06-13|oclc=53177918|isbn=0912756225|lccn=88080672|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Stewart |first=John |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GgULOzNSafMC&pg=PA48#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Early Maps and Surveyors of the City of Washington, D.C. |year=1899 |journal=Records of the Columbia Historical Society |publisher=[[Historical Society of Washington, D.C.|Columbia Historical Society]] |location=Washington, D.C. |volume=2 |pages=48\u201371 |issn=0897-9049 |oclc=40326234 |accessdate=2011-08-15 |via=[[Google Books]]}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_D_ZJBxoCYeAC_2 |title=Standard History of the City of Washington From a Study of the Original Sources |last=Tindall |first=William |location=Knoxville, Tennessee |publisher=H. W. Crew and Company |year=1914 |lccn=14013663|oclc=7059152 |accessdate=2013-01-31 |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/sketchoflifeofbe00tyso/page/n4/mode/1up|title=A sketch of the life of Benjamin Banneker: from notes taken in 1836: read by J. Saurin Norris, before the Maryland Historical Society, October 5th, 1854 |first=Martha Ellicott |last=Tyson |location=Baltimore, Maryland|publisher=Printed for the Maryland Historical Society by John D. Toy |lccn=rc01003357|oclc=85794847|accessdate=2015-04-24|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book|first=Carter Goodwin|last=Woodson|author-link=Carter G. Woodson|year=1919|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U6sQAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA91#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Education of the Negro Prior to 1861: A History of the Education of the Colored People of the United States from the Beginning of Slavery to the Civil War|edition=Second|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=The Associated Publishers, Inc.|lccn=68029024|oclc=1003200476|accessdate=April 15, 2020|via=[[Google Books]]}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Benjamin Banneker}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|History|United States|Maryland}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Banneker, Mythology and legacy of Benjamin}}\n[[Category:African-American culture]]\n[[Category:American folklore]]\n[[Category:Misconceptions]]\n[[Category:Urban legends]]\n[[Category:Legacies by person]]\n", "name_user": "Corker1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistorical marker in Newseum, Washington, DC:editorial change in image legend", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mythology_of_Benjamin_Banneker"}
{"title_page": "Sotra", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Sotra (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Island in Vestland county, Norway}}\n{{Infobox islands\n|name                            = Sotra<br />Store Sotra\n|native_name                     = \n|native_name_link                = \n|sobriquet                       = \n|image_name                      = Sotra-Bergen-Norwegia.JPG\n|image_size                      = \n|image_caption                   = \n|image_alt                       = \n|map_image                       = Norway - Sotra.png\n|pushpin_map                     = Vestland#Norway\n|pushpin_label                   = Sotra\n|pushpin_label_position          = top\n|pushpin_map_alt                 = \n|pushpin_relief                  = \n|pushpin_map_caption             = Location of the island\n|location                        = [[Vestland]], [[Norway]]\n|coordinates                     = {{coord|60.2366|5.0795|display=inline,title|region:NO_type:isle}}\n|area_km2                        = 178.6\n|rank                            = \n|length_km                       = 31\n|width_km                        = 10\n|coastline_km                    = \n|elevation_m                     = 341\n|highest_mount                   = Liat\u00e5rnet\n|country                         = Norway\n|country_admin_divisions_title   = County\n|country_admin_divisions         = [[Vestland]]\n|country_admin_divisions_title_1 = Municipality\n|country_admin_divisions_1       = [[\u00d8ygarden Municipality]]\n|population                      = 19,100<ref name=\"snl\">{{cite web|url=https://snl.no/Store_Sotra|title=Store Sotra|author=Store norske leksikon|authorlink=Store norske leksikon|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2014-12-02}}</ref>\n|population_as_of                = 2017\n|density_km2                     = 106.9\n|density_footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Sotra''' or '''Store Sotra''' is the name of a large [[island]] in [[\u00d8ygarden Municipality]] in [[Vestland]] county, [[Norway]], located just west of the city of [[Bergen]]. It is part of a pair of islands called '[[Store Sotra|Sotra]]' and '[[Litlesotra]]' ('small Sotra') that are part of a large archipelago stretching from [[Fedje (island)|Fedje]] southwards along the coast of Norway.  The larger island of the two is [[Store Sotra]] (also called Sotra), and the smaller (and least populated) of the two is [[Litlesotra]].<ref name=snl />  Roughly 28,700 (2017) people live on the two islands of Sotra, with the larger island having a population of about 19,100 (2017) and 9,589 (2017) living on the smaller island.<ref name=snl />\n\n==Geography==\nThe main population centres on Sotra include (from north to south) Vindenes, [[\u00c5gotnes]], [[Knappskog]], M\u00f8vik, [[T\u00e6lav\u00e5g]], [[Hammarsland]], [[Skogsv\u00e5g]], and [[Klokkarvik]].\n\nThe island of Sotra is part of an [[archipelago]], so it is surrounded by islands and waterways.  To the east of Sotra lies the island of [[Litlesotra]].  The small islands of [[Bild\u00f8y]] and [[Geitung]] lie near Litlesotra.  The [[Raunefjorden]] (to the east) separates Sotra from the mainland [[Bergen Peninsula]].  The small islands of [[Tyss\u00f8yna]], [[Ler\u00f8yna]], and [[Bjelkar\u00f8yna]] lie in the Raunefjorden off the southeastern coast of Sotra.  To the south of Sotra lies the island of [[Toft\u00f8ya]] and the [[Korsfjorden]].  To the west of Sotra lie a number of small islands including [[Algr\u00f8yna]] and [[Lok\u00f8yna]].  Finally, to the north of Sotra lie the small islands of [[Misje]], [[Tur\u00f8yna]], and [[Toft\u00f8yna]].  Sotra is connected to the mainland by a series of road bridges across Bild\u00f8y and Litlesotra before crossing the [[Sotra Bridge]], the seventh-longest suspension bridge in Norway.<ref name=\"snl\" /><ref>{{cite book|last1=Fjell|first1=Ragnvald|title=Sotrabrua|date=1989|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nThe {{convert|341|m|adj=on}} tall Liat\u00e5rnet is the highest mountain on Sotra. Other mountains on the island include the {{convert|285|m|adj=on}} tall [[F\u00f8rdesveten]], the {{convert|112|m|adj=on}} tall [[Gardafjellet]], the {{convert|164|m|adj=on}} tall [[Knappskogfjellet]], and the {{convert|165|m|adj=on}} tall [[Spjeldsfjellet]].\n\n==Media gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:BildoeySotra.jpg|Boathouses at Bild\u00f8y.\nFile:Sotra.jpg|Fishing vessel anchored in a bay.\nFile:PanoramaSotraNese.jpg|View from Liat\u00e5rnet.\nFile:Sotrabrua_2.jpg|Sotra Bridge.\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of Vestland]]\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of Norway]]\n[[Category:\u00d8ygarden]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Vestland]]\n\n\n{{Vestland-island-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Sotra (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Island in Vestland county, Norway}}\n{{Infobox islands\n|name                            = Sotra<br />Store Sotra\n|native_name                     = \n|native_name_link                = \n|sobriquet                       = \n|image_name                      = Sotra-Bergen-Norwegia.JPG\n|image_size                      = \n|image_caption                   = \n|image_alt                       = \n|map_image                       = Norway - Sotra.png\n|pushpin_map                     = Vestland#Norway\n|pushpin_label                   = Sotra\n|pushpin_label_position          = top\n|pushpin_map_alt                 = \n|pushpin_relief                  = \n|pushpin_map_caption             = Location of the island\n|location                        = [[Vestland]], [[Norway]]\n|coordinates                     = {{coord|60.2366|5.0795|display=inline,title|region:NO_type:isle}}\n|area_km2                        = 178.6\n|rank                            = \n|length_km                       = 31\n|width_km                        = 10\n|coastline_km                    = \n|elevation_m                     = 341\n|highest_mount                   = Liat\u00e5rnet\n|country                         = Norway\n|country_admin_divisions_title   = County\n|country_admin_divisions         = [[Vestland]]\n|country_admin_divisions_title_1 = Municipality\n|country_admin_divisions_1       = [[\u00d8ygarden Municipality]]\n|population                      = 19,100<ref name=\"snl\">{{cite web|url=https://snl.no/Store_Sotra|title=Store Sotra|author=Store norske leksikon|authorlink=Store norske leksikon|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2014-12-02}}</ref>\n|population_as_of                = 2017\n|density_km2                     = 106.9\n|density_footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Sotra''' or '''Store Sotra''' is the name of a large [[island]] in [[\u00d8ygarden Municipality]] in [[Vestland]] county, [[Norway]], located just west of the city of [[Bergen]]. It is part of a pair of islands called '[[Store Sotra|Sotra]]' and '[[Litlesotra]]' ('small Sotra') that are part of a large archipelago stretching from [[Fedje (island)|Fedje]] southwards along the coast of Norway.  The larger island of the two is [[Store Sotra]] (also called Sotra), and the smaller (and least populated) of the two is [[Litlesotra]].<ref name=snl />  Roughly 28,700 (2017) people live on the two islands of Sotra, with the larger island having a population of about 19,100 (2017) and 9,589 (2017) living on the smaller island.<ref name=snl />\n\n==Geography==\nThe main population centres on Sotra include (from north to south) [[Vindenes]], [[\u00c5gotnes]], [[Knappskog]], [[M\u00f8vik]], [[T\u00e6lav\u00e5g]], [[Hammarsland]], [[Skogsv\u00e5g]], and [[Klokkarvik]].\n\nThe island of Sotra is part of an [[archipelago]], so it is surrounded by islands and waterways.  To the east of Sotra lies the island of [[Litlesotra]].  The small islands of [[Bild\u00f8y]] and [[Geitung]] lie near Litlesotra.  The [[Raunefjorden]] (to the east) separates Sotra from the mainland [[Bergen Peninsula]].  The small islands of [[Tyss\u00f8yna]], [[Ler\u00f8yna]], and [[Bjelkar\u00f8yna]] lie in the Raunefjorden off the southeastern coast of Sotra.  To the south of Sotra lies the island of [[Toft\u00f8ya]] and the [[Korsfjorden]].  To the west of Sotra lie a number of small islands including [[Algr\u00f8yna]] and [[Lok\u00f8yna]].  Finally, to the north of Sotra lie the small islands of [[Misje]], [[Tur\u00f8yna]], and [[Toft\u00f8yna]].  Sotra is connected to the mainland by a series of road bridges across Bild\u00f8y and Litlesotra before crossing the [[Sotra Bridge]], the seventh-longest suspension bridge in Norway.<ref name=\"snl\" /><ref>{{cite book|last1=Fjell|first1=Ragnvald|title=Sotrabrua|date=1989|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\nThe {{convert|341|m|adj=on}} tall Liat\u00e5rnet is the highest mountain on Sotra. Other mountains on the island include the {{convert|285|m|adj=on}} tall [[F\u00f8rdesveten]], the {{convert|112|m|adj=on}} tall [[Gardafjellet]], the {{convert|164|m|adj=on}} tall [[Knappskogfjellet]], and the {{convert|165|m|adj=on}} tall [[Spjeldsfjellet]].\n\n==Media gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:BildoeySotra.jpg|Boathouses at Bild\u00f8y.\nFile:Sotra.jpg|Fishing vessel anchored in a bay.\nFile:PanoramaSotraNese.jpg|View from Liat\u00e5rnet.\nFile:Sotrabrua_2.jpg|Sotra Bridge.\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of Vestland]]\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of Norway]]\n[[Category:\u00d8ygarden]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Vestland]]\n\n\n{{Vestland-island-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Boreethen", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed wrong links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sotra"}
{"title_page": "Washington Valor", "text_new": "{{short description|Arena football team}}\n{{Infobox indoor American football team\n| name = Washington Valor\n| current =\n| logo =Washington Valor.png\n| helmet = \n| founded = 2016\n| folded = 2019\n| city = [[Capital One Arena]]<br> in [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| misc = [http://www.washingtonvalor.com WashingtonValor.com]\n| uniform = \n| colors = Red, navy blue, silver, white<br />{{color box|#E31837}} {{color box|#002B5C}} {{color box|#C4CED4}} {{color box|#FFFFFF}}\n| coach = [[Benji McDowell]]\n| owner = [[Ted Leonsis|Monumental Sports and Entertainment]]\n| chairman = [[Ted Leonsis]]\n| president = Roger Mody\n| mascot = \n| pastnames = \n| nicknames = \n| league =\n'''[[Arena Football League]] ({{AFL Year|2017}}\u2013{{AFL Year|2019}})'''\n| team_history =\n*'''Washington Valor''' (2017\u20132019)\n| no_league_champs = 1\n| no_conf_champs = 0\n| no_div_champs = 0\n| league_champs = \n*[[ArenaBowl XXXI|2018]]\n| conf_champs = \n| div_champs = \n| playoff_appearances = \n*{{AFL Year|2018}}, {{AFL Year|2019}}\n| no_playoff_appearances = 2\n| arena_years = \n* [[Capital One Arena]] (2017\u20132019)\n}}\n\nThe '''Washington Valor''' were a professional [[arena football]] team based in [[Washington, D.C.]] that played in the [[Arena Football League]] (AFL) from 2017 to 2019. The team's home arena was the [[Capital One Arena]]. The Valor were owned by Monumental Sports and Entertainment ([[Ted Leonsis]], chairman), which also owns the [[Washington Wizards]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA), [[Washington Mystics]] of the [[Women's National Basketball Association]] (WNBA), [[Washington Capitals]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL), [[Capital City Go-Go]] of the [[NBA G League]] and fellow AFL team the [[Baltimore Brigade]].\n\nThe initial announcement was made in February 2016 of being close to a deal. The official announcement was made on March 10, 2016. The team name \"Valor\", and colors of red, white, blue and silver were announced in July 2016. The Valor were the first AFL franchise to play in the DC market since the [[Washington Commandos]] folded in 1990.  The Valor have one Arena Football League title, having defeated fellow Monumental property Baltimore in [[ArenaBowl XXXI]].\n\nFollowing the 2019 season, the AFL ceased operations.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Soul vs Valor (2017) (8).jpg|thumb|left|250px|The [[Capital One Arena|Verizon Center]] in 2017]]\nWashington, D.C. originally had one of the 1987 AFL charter teams called the [[Washington Commandos]]. The team played its home games during its first season at the [[Capital Centre (Landover, Maryland)|Capital Centre]] in [[Landover, Maryland]] in 1987. The Commandos did not play in 1988, but returned as the [[Maryland Commandos]] the following season. The team moved to Virginia in 1990, again as the Washington Commandos and played at the [[Patriot Center]] in [[Fairfax, Virginia]]. The team was folded after the [[1990 Arena Football League season|1990 season]]. Later, [[Washington Redskins]] owner [[Daniel Snyder]] tried to launch an expansion team called the Washington Warriors, but could not get the trademarks<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/articles/30487/warriors-come-in-to-play |title=Warriors, Come In to Play! |author=Dave McKenna |newspaper=Washington City Paper |date=April 29, 1995}}</ref> and was eventually abandoned.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/dc-sports-bog/wp/2016/02/11/13-nickname-suggestions-for-d-c-s-future-arena-football-league-team/ |title=\u2018Washington Maul\u2019 and 12 other name ideas for D.C.\u2019s future Arena Football League team |author=Scott Allen |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=February 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn February 10, 2016, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and radio station [[WTOP-FM]] first broke the story that Monumental Sports and Entertainment ([[Ted Leonsis]], chairman), which also owns the [[National Basketball Association|NBA's]] [[Washington Wizards]], [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA's]] [[Washington Mystics]], and [[National Hockey League|NHL's]] [[Washington Capitals]], were \"close to a deal\" in bringing a new [[Arena Football League]] expansion franchise to the [[Capital One Arena]].<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/digger/wp/2016/02/10/ted-leonsis-close-to-securing-arena-football-league-team-to-play-at-verizon-center/ Ted Leonsis close to securing Arena Football League team to play at Verizon Center], Jonathan O'Connell and Dan Steinberg, ''Washington Post'', February 10, 2016</ref><ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/dc-sports-bog/wp/2016/03/10/ted-leonsis-to-announce-d-c-is-getting-an-arena-football-league-team/?platform=hootsuite Ted Leonsis to announce D.C. is getting an Arena Football League team], Scott Allen, ''The Washington Post'', March 10, 2016</ref>  On March 10, 2016, AFL commissioner [[Scott Butera]] announced that the deal was finalized and that the new Washington, D.C., team would begin play in 2017.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160517012036/http://www.arenafootball.com:80/sports/a-footbl/spec-rel/031016aaa.html AFL Lands New Team in Nation's Capital], ArenaFootball.com, March 10, 2016</ref> The official website, Facebook and Twitter pages launched on March 15, 2016. On July 14, 2016, the team's name was announced as the Washington Valor with the team's colors being red, white and blue.<ref>{{cite news|last=Russell |first=Jake |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/dc-sports-bog/wp/2016/07/14/and-the-name-of-d-c-s-arena-football-team-is-the-washington-valor/ |title=And the name of D.C.\u2019s arena football team is \u2026 the Washington Valor |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=2016-08-26}}</ref> Jerseys and helmets designs were released on December 10, 2016. Valor owners Monument Sports and Entertainment also acquired a franchise in Baltimore on November 14, 2016.<ref>[http://www.monumentalsports.com/newsroom/2016/11/monumental-sports-entertainment-acquires-afl-team-to-play-in-baltimore NEWSROOM MONUMENTAL SPORTS & ENTERTAINMENT ACQUIRES AFL TEAM TO PLAY IN BALTIMORE], Monumental Sports and Entertainment website, November 14, 2016</ref> The team's name was later revealed as the [[Baltimore Brigade]]. The Valor's first game was on April 7, 2017, in the Verizon Center against the Brigade. The Valor were the first AFL franchise to play in the DC market since the Commandos.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/dc-sports-bog/wp/2016/03/10/ted-leonsis-to-announce-d-c-is-getting-an-arena-football-league-team |title=Ted Leonsis to announce D.C. is getting an Arena Football League team |author=Scott Allen |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=March 10, 2016}}</ref> On July 28, 2018 the Washington Valor upset the Baltimore Brigade 69-55 at [[Royal Farms Arena]] in Baltimore in [[Arena Bowl XXXI]], despite having won only two regular-season games in [[2018 Arena Football League season|2018]].  Washington QB [[Arvell Nelson]] was named the game's Most Valuable Player.\n\nIn a January 2019 interview with ''[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]'', Leonsis noted that the Valor were not particularly successful in regard to finances, and that he mainly used the team and its Baltimore counterpart to experiment with ideas to later use with his more prominent sports properties such as the Wizards, Mystics, and Capitals.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/patrickmurray/2019/01/17/nba-london-2019-washington-wizards-owner-ted-leonsis-on-why-the-nba-is-the-most-valuable-league/#5478dab73733 NBA London 2019: Wizards owner Ted Leonsis on why the NBA is the most valuable league]. ''Forbes'' (January 17, 2019). Retrieved January 18, 2019.</ref> Following the 2019 season, the AFL announced it had shut down the operations of local teams and was looking into becoming a traveling league. However, the league filed for bankruptcy and ceased operations entirely in November 2019.\n\n[[File:Soul vs Valor (2017) (7).jpg|thumb|350px|The Valor playing the [[Philadelphia Soul]] in 2017]]\n\n==Coaches and personnel==\n\n===Head coaches===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:140px;\"|Name\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Term\n! colspan=\"3\" | Regular season\n! colspan=\"3\" |Playoffs\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Awards\n|-\n! W\n! L\n! Win%\n! W\n! L\n! Win%\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Dean Cokinos]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{AFL Year|2017}}\u2013{{AFL Year|2018}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|15\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{winpct|3|15}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{winpct|0|0}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Benji McDowell]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{AFL Year|2018}}\u2013{{AFL Year|2019}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|9\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{winpct|9|11}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{winpct|2|3}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|}\n\n===Staff===\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n|-\n! colspan=7 style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Washington Valor|border=2}}; text-align:center;\" | Washington Valor staff\n|-\n|colspan=7 align=\"right\" |\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|\n| style=\"font-size: 95%;\" valign=\"top\" | '''Front Office'''\n*Chairman \u2013 \t[[Ted Leonsis]]\n*President \u2013 Roger Mody\n\n|width=\"35\"|&nbsp;\n|valign=\"top\"|\n| style=\"font-size: 95%;\" valign=\"top\" | '''Coaches'''\n\n*Head Coach \u2013 [[Benji McDowell]]\n*Offensive Coordinator \u2013 vacant\n*Defensive Coordinator \u2013 Benji McDowell\n*Player Coordinator \u2013 Cos Dematteo\n*Strength and Conditioning \u2013 Ben Jenkins\n*Team Physician - Dr. Jeffrey Mayer, MD\n\n|}\n\n==Season-by-season results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"margin:center; font-size:75%;\"\n|bgcolor=\"#FFCCCC\"|'''[[List of ArenaBowl champions|ArenaBowl Champions]]'''\n|bgcolor=\"#DDFFDD\"|'''ArenaBowl Appearance'''\n|bgcolor=\"#D0E7FF\"|'''Division Champions'''\n|bgcolor=\"#96CDCD\"|'''Playoff Berth'''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; width:70%;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:5%;\"|[[List of Arena Football League seasons|Season]]\n!rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:5%;\"|[[List of leagues of American football|League]]\n!rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:5%;\"|Conference\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Division\n!colspan=\"3\"|Regular season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Postseason results\n|-\n!Finish\n!Wins\n!Losses\n|-\n|align=\"center\" Colspan=\"8\" style=\"background: #E31837\"|'''<span style=\"color: #FFFFFF\">Washington Valor</span>'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|{{afly|2017}}\n|align=\"center\"|AFL\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|5th\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|align=\"center\"|11\n|\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|{{afly|2018}}\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#FFCCCC\"|AFL\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#DDFFDD\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#96CDCD\"|4th\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|bgcolor=\"FFCCCC\"|'''Won semifinals ([[Albany Empire (AFL)|Albany]]) <br> Won [[ArenaBowl XXXI]] ([[Baltimore Brigade|Baltimore]])\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|{{afly|2019}}\n|align=\"center\"|AFL\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#96CDCD\"|2nd\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|Lost in Playoffs ([[Philadelphia Soul|Philadelphia]])\n|-\n!align=\"center\" rowSpan=\"3\" colSpan=\"5\"|Total\n|align=\"center\"|'''12'''\n|align=\"center\"|'''26'''\n|colSpan=\"2\"|'''(includes only regular season)'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|'''2'''\n|align=\"center\"|'''3'''\n|colSpan=\"2\"|'''(includes only the postseason)'''\n|-\n!align=\"center\"|15\n!align=\"center\"|29\n|colSpan=\"2\"|'''(includes both regular season and postseason)'''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Washington Commandos]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.washingtonvalor.com Official website]\n\n{{Washington Valor}}\n{{Arena Football League}}\n\n[[Category:Washington Valor| ]]\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:2019 disestablishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Arena football team}}\n{{Infobox indoor American football team\n| name = Washington Valor\n| current =\n| logo =Washington Valor.png\n| helmet = \n| founded = 2016\n| folded = 2019\n| city = [[Capital One Arena]]<br> in [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| misc = [http://www.washingtonvalor.com WashingtonValor.com]\n| uniform = \n| colors = Red, navy blue, silver, white<br />{{color box|#E31837}} {{color box|#002B5C}} {{color box|#C4CED4}} {{color box|#FFFFFF}}\n| coach = [[Benji McDowell]]\n| owner = [[Ted Leonsis|Monumental Sports and Entertainment]]\n| chairman = [[Ted Leonsis]]\n| president = Roger Mody\n| mascot = \n| pastnames = \n| nicknames = \n| league =\n'''[[Arena Football League]] ({{AFL Year|2017}}\u2013{{AFL Year|2019}})'''\n| team_history =\n*'''Washington Valor''' (2017\u20132019)\n| no_league_champs = 1\n| no_conf_champs = 0\n| no_div_champs = 0\n| league_champs = \n*[[ArenaBowl XXXI|2018]]\n| conf_champs = \n| div_champs = \n| playoff_appearances = \n*{{AFL Year|2018}}, {{AFL Year|2019}}\n| no_playoff_appearances = 2\n| arena_years = \n* [[Capital One Arena]] (2017\u20132019)\n}}\n\nThe '''Washington Valor''' were a professional [[arena football]] team based in [[Washington, D.C.]] that played in the [[Arena Football League]] (AFL) from 2017 to 2019. The team's home arena was the [[Capital One Arena]]. The Valor were owned by Monumental Sports and Entertainment ([[Ted Leonsis]], chairman), which also owns the [[Washington Wizards]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA), [[Washington Mystics]] of the [[Women's National Basketball Association]] (WNBA), [[Washington Capitals]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL), [[Capital City Go-Go]] of the [[NBA G League]] and fellow AFL team the [[Baltimore Brigade]].\n\nThe initial announcement was made in February 2016 of being close to a deal. The official announcement was made in March 10, 2016. The team name \"Valor\", and colors of red, white, blue and silver were announced in July 2016. The Valor were the first AFL franchise to play in the DC market since the [[Washington Commandos]] folded in 1990.  The Valor have one Arena Football League title, having defeated fellow Monumental property Baltimore in [[ArenaBowl XXXI]].\n\nFollowing the 2019 season, the AFL ceased operations.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Soul vs Valor (2017) (8).jpg|thumb|left|250px|The [[Capital One Arena|Verizon Center]] in 2017]]\nWashington, D.C. originally had one of the 1987 AFL charter teams called the [[Washington Commandos]]. The team played its home games during its first season at the [[Capital Centre (Landover, Maryland)|Capital Centre]] in [[Landover, Maryland]] in 1987. The Commandos did not play in 1988, but returned as the [[Maryland Commandos]] the following season. The team moved to Virginia in 1990, again as the Washington Commandos and played at the [[Patriot Center]] in [[Fairfax, Virginia]]. The team was folded after the [[1990 Arena Football League season|1990 season]]. Later, [[Washington Redskins]] owner [[Daniel Snyder]] tried to launch an expansion team called the Washington Warriors, but could not get the trademarks<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/articles/30487/warriors-come-in-to-play |title=Warriors, Come In to Play! |author=Dave McKenna |newspaper=Washington City Paper |date=April 29, 1995}}</ref> and was eventually abandoned.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/dc-sports-bog/wp/2016/02/11/13-nickname-suggestions-for-d-c-s-future-arena-football-league-team/ |title=\u2018Washington Maul\u2019 and 12 other name ideas for D.C.\u2019s future Arena Football League team |author=Scott Allen |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=February 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn February 10, 2016, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and radio station [[WTOP-FM]] first broke the story that Monumental Sports and Entertainment ([[Ted Leonsis]], chairman), which also owns the [[National Basketball Association|NBA's]] [[Washington Wizards]], [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA's]] [[Washington Mystics]], and [[National Hockey League|NHL's]] [[Washington Capitals]], were \"close to a deal\" in bringing a new [[Arena Football League]] expansion franchise to the [[Capital One Arena]].<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/digger/wp/2016/02/10/ted-leonsis-close-to-securing-arena-football-league-team-to-play-at-verizon-center/ Ted Leonsis close to securing Arena Football League team to play at Verizon Center], Jonathan O'Connell and Dan Steinberg, ''Washington Post'', February 10, 2016</ref><ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/dc-sports-bog/wp/2016/03/10/ted-leonsis-to-announce-d-c-is-getting-an-arena-football-league-team/?platform=hootsuite Ted Leonsis to announce D.C. is getting an Arena Football League team], Scott Allen, ''The Washington Post'', March 10, 2016</ref>  On March 10, 2016, AFL commissioner [[Scott Butera]] announced that the deal was finalized and that the new Washington, D.C., team would begin play in 2017.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160517012036/http://www.arenafootball.com:80/sports/a-footbl/spec-rel/031016aaa.html AFL Lands New Team in Nation's Capital], ArenaFootball.com, March 10, 2016</ref> The official website, Facebook and Twitter pages launched on March 15, 2016. On July 14, 2016, the teams name was announced as the Washington Valor with the teams colors being red, white and blue.<ref>{{cite news|last=Russell |first=Jake |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/dc-sports-bog/wp/2016/07/14/and-the-name-of-d-c-s-arena-football-team-is-the-washington-valor/ |title=And the name of D.C.\u2019s arena football team is \u2026 the Washington Valor |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=2016-08-26}}</ref> Jerseys and helmets designs were released on December 10, 2016. Valor owners Monument Sports and Entertainment also acquired a franchise in Baltimore on November 14, 2016.<ref>[http://www.monumentalsports.com/newsroom/2016/11/monumental-sports-entertainment-acquires-afl-team-to-play-in-baltimore NEWSROOM MONUMENTAL SPORTS & ENTERTAINMENT ACQUIRES AFL TEAM TO PLAY IN BALTIMORE], Monumental Sports and Entertainment website, November 14, 2016</ref> The team's name was later revealed as the [[Baltimore Brigade]]. The Valor's first game was on April 7, 2017, in the Verizon Center against the Brigade. The Valor were the first AFL franchise to play in the DC market since the Commandos.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/dc-sports-bog/wp/2016/03/10/ted-leonsis-to-announce-d-c-is-getting-an-arena-football-league-team |title=Ted Leonsis to announce D.C. is getting an Arena Football League team |author=Scott Allen |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=March 10, 2016}}</ref> On July 28, 2018 the Washington Valor upset the Baltimore Brigade 69-55 at [[Royal Farms Arena]] in Baltimore in [[Arena Bowl XXXI]], despite having won only two regular-season games in [[2018 Arena Football League season|2018]].  Washington QB [[Arvell Nelson]] was named the game's Most Valuable Player.\n\nIn a January 2019 interview with ''[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]'', Leonsis noted that the Valor were not particularly successful in regard to finances, and that he mainly used the team and its Baltimore counterpart to experiment with ideas to later use with his more prominent sports properties such as the Wizards, Mystics, and Capitals.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/patrickmurray/2019/01/17/nba-london-2019-washington-wizards-owner-ted-leonsis-on-why-the-nba-is-the-most-valuable-league/#5478dab73733 NBA London 2019: Wizards owner Ted Leonsis on why the NBA is the most valuable league]. ''Forbes'' (January 17, 2019). Retrieved January 18, 2019.</ref> Following the 2019 season, the AFL announced it had shut down the operations of local teams and was looking into becoming a traveling league. However, the league filed for bankruptcy and ceased operations entirely in November 2019.\n\n[[File:Soul vs Valor (2017) (7).jpg|thumb|350px|The Valor playing the [[Philadelphia Soul]] in 2017]]\n\n==Coaches and personnel==\n\n===Head coaches===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:140px;\"|Name\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Term\n! colspan=\"3\" | Regular season\n! colspan=\"3\" |Playoffs\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Awards\n|-\n! W\n! L\n! Win%\n! W\n! L\n! Win%\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Dean Cokinos]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{AFL Year|2017}}\u2013{{AFL Year|2018}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|15\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{winpct|3|15}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{winpct|0|0}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Benji McDowell]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{AFL Year|2018}}\u2013{{AFL Year|2019}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|9\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{winpct|9|11}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{winpct|2|3}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|}\n\n===Staff===\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n|-\n! colspan=7 style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Washington Valor|border=2}}; text-align:center;\" | Washington Valor staff\n|-\n|colspan=7 align=\"right\" |\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|\n| style=\"font-size: 95%;\" valign=\"top\" | '''Front Office'''\n*Chairman \u2013 \t[[Ted Leonsis]]\n*President \u2013 Roger Mody\n\n|width=\"35\"|&nbsp;\n|valign=\"top\"|\n| style=\"font-size: 95%;\" valign=\"top\" | '''Coaches'''\n\n*Head Coach \u2013 [[Benji McDowell]]\n*Offensive Coordinator \u2013 vacant\n*Defensive Coordinator \u2013 Benji McDowell\n*Player Coordinator \u2013 Cos Dematteo\n*Strength and Conditioning \u2013 Ben Jenkins\n*Team Physician - Dr. Jeffrey Mayer, MD\n\n|}\n\n==Season-by-season results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"margin:center; font-size:75%;\"\n|bgcolor=\"#FFCCCC\"|'''[[List of ArenaBowl champions|ArenaBowl Champions]]'''\n|bgcolor=\"#DDFFDD\"|'''ArenaBowl Appearance'''\n|bgcolor=\"#D0E7FF\"|'''Division Champions'''\n|bgcolor=\"#96CDCD\"|'''Playoff Berth'''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; width:70%;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:5%;\"|[[List of Arena Football League seasons|Season]]\n!rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:5%;\"|[[List of leagues of American football|League]]\n!rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:5%;\"|Conference\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Division\n!colspan=\"3\"|Regular season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Postseason results\n|-\n!Finish\n!Wins\n!Losses\n|-\n|align=\"center\" Colspan=\"8\" style=\"background: #E31837\"|'''<span style=\"color: #FFFFFF\">Washington Valor</span>'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|{{afly|2017}}\n|align=\"center\"|AFL\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|5th\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|align=\"center\"|11\n|\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|{{afly|2018}}\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#FFCCCC\"|AFL\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#DDFFDD\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#96CDCD\"|4th\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|bgcolor=\"FFCCCC\"|'''Won semifinals ([[Albany Empire (AFL)|Albany]]) <br> Won [[ArenaBowl XXXI]] ([[Baltimore Brigade|Baltimore]])\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|{{afly|2019}}\n|align=\"center\"|AFL\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#96CDCD\"|2nd\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|Lost in Playoffs ([[Philadelphia Soul|Philadelphia]])\n|-\n!align=\"center\" rowSpan=\"3\" colSpan=\"5\"|Total\n|align=\"center\"|'''12'''\n|align=\"center\"|'''26'''\n|colSpan=\"2\"|'''(includes only regular season)'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|'