ies)}}\n[[Category:2010s American crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:2017 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Ozarks in fiction]]\n[[Category:Serial drama television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by Media Rights Capital]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Works about Mexican drug cartels]]\n", "name_user": "Pdelva", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSeason 3 (2020):tweak to plot description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ozark_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Habla Ahora", "text_new": "{{short description|album by Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 Loyola Anaya}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Habla Ahora\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 (singer)|Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9]]\n| cover      = File:Maria_Jose_Habla_Ahora_Cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 21, 2016\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Latin pop]], [[Pop music|pop]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Grupo CIE|Sei Track Musica]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[De Noche]]\n| prev_year  = 2012\n| next_title = [[Conexi\u00f3n (Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 album)|Conexi\u00f3n]]\n| next_year  = 2019\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Special Edition Cover\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = Habla_Ahora_Edicion_Especial.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption =\n}}\n{{Singles\n | name        = Habla Ahora\n | type        = album\n | single1     = [[Las Qu\u00e9 Se Ponen Bien La Falda]]\n | single1date = May 13, 2016\n | single2     = Habla Ahora\n | single2date = September 9, 2016\n | single3     = Lo Que Te Mereces\n | single3date = March 10, 2017\n | single4     = El Amor Coloca\n | single4date = April 20, 2017\n | single5     = Duri Duri\n | single5date = September 5, 2017\n}}\n}}\n'''''Habla Ahora''''' is the fifth studio album by [[Mexican people|Mexican]] singer [[Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 (singer)|Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9]]. The follow up to [[De Noche]], the album introduces new genres to the singer. The lead single \"[[Las Qu\u00e9 Se Ponen Bien La Falda]]\" marks the first time the singer dwells into the genre of reggaeton and urban music, while the album's title track incorporates a bachata undertone. She also continues what now is known as one of her trademarks and includes two covers on the album. \"Olvidame Y Pega la Vuelta\" which features Bryan Amadeus is originally a song by [[Pimpinela]], as well as \"Duri Duri\" which is originally sung by 80's High Energy Spanish band Click.\n\nOn May 28, 2017, the album was re-released digitally as a special edition. It debuted at the fifth position on the Pop Album's in Spanish.<ref>http://seitrack.mx/maria-jose-debuto-en-el-5-de-itunes-con-la-edicion-especial-de-habla-ahora/{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The new edition features all 12 of the original track listing plus 3 new songs and a remix. The new material includes the songs \"Ni me vas a Extra\u00f1ar\" (You won't even miss me), \"Despertar\" (Waking Up) as well as the fourth single off the album \"El Amor Coloca\" along with a remix version.\n\n==Background==\nIn 2012, Jos\u00e9 released her fourth studio album, ''[[De Noche]]'', which was very successful.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entretenimiento.starmedia.com/musica/lista-canciones-disco-noche-maria-jose.html|title=Lista de canciones del disco \"De Noche\" de Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9|author=Mor\u00e1n, B\u00e1rbara|work=[[Starmedia]]|publisher=Orange Horizons Latina, S.A. de C.V|date=14 August 2012|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref> \"T\u00fa Ya Sabes A M\u00ed\" served as the lead single for the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://videos.starmedia.com/entretenimiento/tu-ya-sabes-mi-nuevo-video-maria-jose.html|title=T\u00fa ya sabes a M\u00ed\", nuevo video de Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9|author=Mor\u00e1n, B\u00e1rbara|work=[[Starmedia]]|publisher=Orange Horizons Latina, S.A. de C.V|date=29 June 2012|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref> In 2014, Jos\u00e9 became impregnated by her husband,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peopleenespanol.com/article/la-ex-kabah-maria-jose-esta-embarazada|title=La ex Kabah Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 est\u00e1 embarazada|work=[[People en Espa\u00f1ol]]|publisher=[[Time Inc]]|date=6 February 2014|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref> later taking hiatus from her musical career to focus on her baby.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eltijuanense.com/reflector/musica/31981-estrena-maria-jose-video-oficial-de-las-que-se-ponen-bien-la-falda|title=Estrena Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 v\u00eddeo oficial de \"Las que se ponen bien la falda|work=El Tijuanese|date=22 May 2016|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref> In 2015, Jos\u00e9 embarked on a tour with [[OV7]] and [[Kabah (band)|Kabah]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.debate.com.mx/show/La-Josa-alza-la-voz-a-favor-de-las-mujeres-con-tema---20160620-0155.html|title=La Josa\" alza la voz a favor de las mujeres con tema|work=El Debate|author=Rodarte, Jorge|publisher=|date=20 June 2016|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref> Following the split between her and the two groups, she then began recording material for her future studio project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/articulo/espectaculos/musica/2016/06/17/maria-jose-se-despide-de-kabah-y-ov7|title=Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 se despide de Kabah y OV7|work=El Universal|publisher=Compa\u00f1\u00eda Period\u00edstica Nacional S. A. de C. V|date=17 July 2016|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Singles ==\n*\"[[Las Qu\u00e9 Se Ponen Bien La Falda]]\" was released as the lead single from the album. Debuting to radio and digital retailers on May 9, 2016, and features Puerto Rican singer [[Ivy Queen]]. Jos\u00e9 premiered snippets of the song on her social networks in April 2016. On 30 April 2016, a preview of the song was posted on Jos\u00e9's official YouTube and VEVO accounts. Las Que Se Ponen Bien La Falda marks the first time for the singer to explore new genres into urban and reggaeton, a complete departure from her previous singles and material.\n*\"Habla Ahora\", the album's title track, was released as the album's second single impacting radio on September 9, 2016. It also introduces Josa to new genres of music with the song incorporating Bachata undertones throughout the main chorus of the song.\n*\"Lo Que Te Mereces\" was released on March 27, 2017 as the album's third single. The song was co-written by Mexican singer-songwriter [[Paty Cantu]] and marks the fourth time the two work together on a song, the past songs including \"Prefiero Ser Su Amante\" which was the third single from her past album [[De Noche]].\n*\"El Amor Coloca\" was released on April 20, 2017 as the lead single from the re-release of the album as well as the fourth single over all. Following her trademark, the song is a cover originally a song from Spanish singer [[Monica Naranjo]].\n*\u201dDuri Duri\u201d was released as the album's fifth single on September 7, 2017 same day as the premiere of its music video.\n\n===Promotional Singles===\nAlthough not released as a single, \"Olvidame Y Pega la Vuelta\" received heavy rotation on Mexican radio due to the singer filming a music video for the song.\n\n== Tour ==\nMar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 embarked on the Lo Que Te Merces Tour in support of her fifth album ''Habla Ahora''. Beginning in Mexico, the tour will also visit parts of the United States. The name is borrowed from the album's third single.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = ''Habla Ahora''\n\n| title1 = [[Las Qu\u00e9 Se Ponen Bien La Falda]] <small>(featuring [[Ivy Queen]])</small>\n| length1 = 3:45\n\n| title2 = Lo Que Te Mereces\n| length2 = 4:10\n\n| title3 = [[Olvidame y Pega la Vuelta]] </small>(featuring Bryan Amadeus)</small>\n| length3 = 3:25\n\n| title4 = Cobarde\n| length4 = 3:25\n\n| title5 = Habla Ahora\n| length5 = 3:22\n\n| title6 = Quiero que te Quedes\n| length6 = 3:46\n\n| title7 = Nada Fue Verdad\n| length7 = 3:38\n\n| title8 = Duri Duri\n| length8 = 3:36\n\n| title9 = Ella Me Gusta para Ti\n| length9 = 3:09\n\n| title10 = No Soy <small>(featuring [[Yuridia]])</small>\n| length10 = 3:16\n\n| title11 = Hombre Malvado\n| length11 = 2:34\n\n| title12 = [[Las Qu\u00e9 Se Ponen Bien La Falda]] </small>[Pop Version] (featuring [[Ivy Queen]])</small>\n| length12 = 3:58\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = ''Habla Ahora''{{nobold|&nbsp;\u2014 Special Edition (Bonus tracks)}}\n| collapsed = yes\n\n| title13 = Ni Me Vas a Extra\u00f1ar\n| length13 = 2:55\n\n| title14 = Despertar\n| length14 = 3:35\n\n| title15 = El Amor Coloca\n| length15 = 3:24\n\n| title16 = El Amor Coloca (Remix)\n| length16 = 3:26\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9}}\n\n[[Category:Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 (singer) albums]]\n[[Category:2016 albums]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|album by Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 Loyola Anaya}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Habla Ahora\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 (singer)|Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9]]\n| cover      = File:Maria_Jose_Habla_Ahora_Cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 21, 2016\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Latin pop]], [[Pop music|pop]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Grupo CIE|Sei Track Musica]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[De Noche]]\n| prev_year  = 2012\n| next_title = [[Conexi\u00f3n (Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 album)|Conexi\u00f3n]]\n| next_year  = 2019\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Special Edition Cover\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = Habla_Ahora_Edicion_Especial.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption =\n}}\n{{Singles\n | name        = Habla Ahora\n | type        = album\n | single1     = [[Las Qu\u00e9 Se Ponen Bien La Falda]]\n | single1date = May 13, 2016\n | single2     = Habla Ahora\n | single2date = September 9, 2016\n | single3     = Lo Que Te Mereces\n | single3date = March 10, 2017\n | single4     = El Amor Coloca\n | single4date = April 20, 2017\n | single5     = Duri Duri\n | single5date = September 5, 2017\n}}\n}}\n'''''Habla Ahora''''' is the fifth studio album by [[Mexican people|Mexican]] singer [[Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 (singer)|Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9]]. The follow up to [[De Noche]], the album introduces new genres to the singer. The lead single \"[[Las Qu\u00e9 Se Ponen Bien La Falda]]\" marks the first time the singer dwells into the genre of reggaeton and urban music, while the album's title track incorporates a bachata undertone. She also continues what now is known as one of her trademarks and includes two covers on the album. \"Olvidame Y Pega la Vuelta\" which features Bryan Amadeus is originally a song by [[Pimpinela]], as well as \"Duri Duri\" which is originally sung by 80's High Energy Spanish band Click.\n\nOn May 28, 2017, the album was re-released digitally as a special edition. It debuted at the fifth position on the Pop Album's in Spanish.<ref>http://seitrack.mx/maria-jose-debuto-en-el-5-de-itunes-con-la-edicion-especial-de-habla-ahora/{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The new edition features all 12 of the original track listing plus 3 new songs and a remix. The new material includes the songs \"Ni me vas a Extra\u00f1ar\" (You won't even miss me), \"Despertar\" (Waking Up) as well as the fourth single off the album \"El Amor Coloca\" along with a remix version.\n\n==Background==\nIn 2012, Jos\u00e9 released her fourth studio album, ''[[De Noche]]'', which was very successful.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entretenimiento.starmedia.com/musica/lista-canciones-disco-noche-maria-jose.html|title=Lista de canciones del disco \"De Noche\" de Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9|author=Mor\u00e1n, B\u00e1rbara|work=[[Starmedia]]|publisher=Orange Horizons Latina, S.A. de C.V|date=14 August 2012|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref> \"T\u00fa Ya Sabes A M\u00ed\" served as the lead single for the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://videos.starmedia.com/entretenimiento/tu-ya-sabes-mi-nuevo-video-maria-jose.html|title=T\u00fa ya sabes a M\u00ed\", nuevo video de Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9|author=Mor\u00e1n, B\u00e1rbara|work=[[Starmedia]]|publisher=Orange Horizons Latina, S.A. de C.V|date=29 June 2012|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref> In 2014, Jos\u00e9 became impregnated by her husband,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peopleenespanol.com/article/la-ex-kabah-maria-jose-esta-embarazada|title=La ex Kabah Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 est\u00e1 embarazada|work=[[People en Espa\u00f1ol]]|publisher=[[Time Inc]]|date=6 February 2014|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref> later taking hiatus from her musical career to focus on her baby.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eltijuanense.com/reflector/musica/31981-estrena-maria-jose-video-oficial-de-las-que-se-ponen-bien-la-falda|title=Estrena Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 v\u00eddeo oficial de \"Las que se ponen bien la falda|work=El Tijuanese|date=22 May 2016|accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref> In 2015, Jos\u00e9 embarked on a tour with [[OV7]] and [[Kabah (band)|Kabah]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.debate.com.mx/show/La-Josa-alza-la-voz-a-favor-de-las-mujeres-con-tema---20160620-0155.html|title=La Josa\" alza la voz a favor de las mujeres con tema|work=El Debate|author=Rodarte, Jorge|publisher=|date=20 June 2016|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref> Following the split between her and the two groups, she then began recording material for her future studio project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/articulo/espectaculos/musica/2016/06/17/maria-jose-se-despide-de-kabah-y-ov7|title=Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 se despide de Kabah y OV7|work=El Universal|publisher=Compa\u00f1\u00eda Period\u00edstica Nacional S. A. de C. V|date=17 July 2016|accessdate=20 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Singles ==\n*\"[[Las Qu\u00e9 Se Ponen Bien La Falda]]\" was released as the lead single from the album. Debuting to radio and digital retailers on May 9, 2016, and features Puerto Rican singer [[Ivy Queen]]. Jos\u00e9 premiered snippets of the song on her social networks in April 2016. On 30 April 2016, a preview of the song was posted on Jos\u00e9's official YouTube and VEVO accounts. Las Que Se Ponen Bien La Falda marks the first time for the singer to explore new genres into urban and reggaeton, a complete departure from her previous singles and material.\n*\"Habla Ahora\", the album's title track, was released as the album's second single impacting radio on September 9, 2016. It also introduces Josa to new genres of music with the song incorporating Bachata undertones throughout the main chorus of the song.\n*\"Lo Que Te Mereces\" was released on March 27, 2017 as the album's third single. The song was co-written by Mexican singer-songwriter [[Paty Cantu]] and marks the fourth time the two work together on a song, the past songs including \"Prefiero Ser Su Amante\" which was the third single from her past album [[De Noche]].\n*\"El Amor Coloca\" was released on April 20, 2017 as the lead single from the re-release of the album as well as the fourth single over all. Following her trademark, the song is a cover originally a song from Spanish singer [[Monica Naranjo]].\n*\u201dDuri Duri\u201d was released as the album's fifth single on September 7, 2017 same day as the premiere of its music video.\n\n===Promotional Singles===\nAlthough not released as a single, \"Olvidame Y Pega la Vuelta\" received heavy rotation on Mexican radio due to the singer filming a music video for the song.\n\n== Tour ==\nMar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 embarked on the [[Lo Que Te Mereces Tour|Lo Que Te Merces Tour]] in support of her fifth album ''Habla Ahora''. Beginning in Mexico, the tour will also visit parts of the United States. The name is borrowed from the album's third single.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = ''Habla Ahora''\n\n| title1 = [[Las Qu\u00e9 Se Ponen Bien La Falda]] <small>(featuring [[Ivy Queen]])</small>\n| length1 = 3:45\n\n| title2 = Lo Que Te Mereces\n| length2 = 4:10\n\n| title3 = [[Olvidame y Pega la Vuelta]] </small>(featuring Bryan Amadeus)</small>\n| length3 = 3:25\n\n| title4 = Cobarde\n| length4 = 3:25\n\n| title5 = Habla Ahora\n| length5 = 3:22\n\n| title6 = Quiero que te Quedes\n| length6 = 3:46\n\n| title7 = Nada Fue Verdad\n| length7 = 3:38\n\n| title8 = Duri Duri\n| length8 = 3:36\n\n| title9 = Ella Me Gusta para Ti\n| length9 = 3:09\n\n| title10 = No Soy <small>(featuring [[Yuridia]])</small>\n| length10 = 3:16\n\n| title11 = Hombre Malvado\n| length11 = 2:34\n\n| title12 = [[Las Qu\u00e9 Se Ponen Bien La Falda]] </small>[Pop Version] (featuring [[Ivy Queen]])</small>\n| length12 = 3:58\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = ''Habla Ahora''{{nobold|&nbsp;\u2014 Special Edition (Bonus tracks)}}\n| collapsed = yes\n\n| title13 = Ni Me Vas a Extra\u00f1ar\n| length13 = 2:55\n\n| title14 = Despertar\n| length14 = 3:35\n\n| title15 = El Amor Coloca\n| length15 = 3:24\n\n| title16 = El Amor Coloca (Remix)\n| length16 = 3:26\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9}}\n\n[[Category:Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 (singer) albums]]\n[[Category:2016 albums]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language albums]]\n", "name_user": "Nosebagbear", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Lo Que Te Mereces Tour (2nd nomination)closed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habla_Ahora"}
{"title_page": "Dave Catching", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{one source|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Dave Catching\n| image                 = Dave Catching playing with the Eagles of Death Metal at the Commodore Ballroom July 20th 2009.jpg\n| caption            = Dave Catching performing with the [[Eagles of Death Metal]] at the Commodore Ballroom in [[Vancouver, British Columbia]]\n| image_size            = 250\n| landscape           = Yes\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = David Catching\n| alias               = Diamond Dave<br>Darlin' Dave <br> Davey Jo <br> Snohawk \n| birth_date      =  {{birth date and age|1961|6|7}}\n| origin              = [[Memphis, Tennessee]], US\n| genre               = [[Stoner rock]], [[hard rock]], [[Palm Desert Scene|desert rock]], [[garage rock revival]], [[acid rock]], [[psychedelic rock]], [[blues rock]]\n| occupation          = Musician, songwriter, producer\n| years_active        = 1982\u2013present\n| instrument          = Vocals, guitar, bass guitar, piano, keyboard, [[lap steel]], [[twelve-string guitar]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Queens of the Stone Age]], [[Eagles of Death Metal]], [[Tex & the Horseheads]], The Ringling Sisters, [[Mojave Lords]], [[earthlings?]], [[Mark Lanegan]], Gnarltones, Pink Slip, [[Mondo Generator]], [[Smith & Pyle]], [[Masters of Reality]], Star & Dagger, [[Peaches (musician)|Peaches]], [[The Mutants (musical collaboration)|The Mutants]]\n}}\n\n'''David Catching''' (born June 7, 1961) is an American musician and producer from [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], [[Tennessee]]. He is a founding member of the California [[stoner rock]] band [[earthlings?]], a touring member of [[Eagles of Death Metal]] and the co-founder of the [[Rancho De La Luna]] recording studio.\n\n[[File:Catching1.jpg|thumb|220px|alt=text|Dave Catching playing with [[Eagles of Death Metal]] live at The Glass House February 8, 2006]]\n\n==Recording career==\nCatching has played the guitar for well-known hard rock bands [[Eagles of Death Metal]], [[Queens of the Stone Age]], [[Tex and the Horseheads]], The Ringling Sisters, [[earthlings?]], [[Mondo Generator]] and the [[Masters of Reality]]. He is also a member of [[Yellow No. 5 (band)|Yellow #5]], and the Gnarltones.\n\nCatching has been associated with the desert country rock band, [[Smith & Pyle]]. He contributed to the debut album of country rock duo [[Smith & Pyle]], ''It's OK to be Happy'', which was recorded at [[Rancho de la Luna]] and released in 2008. He currently resides in [[Joshua Tree, California]].\n\nCatching was on stage with Eagles of Death Metal during the [[November 2015 Paris attacks]], and escaped the [[Bataclan (theatre)|Bataclan]] with the rest of the band.\n\n==Musical equipment==\nWith the Eagles of Death Metal, Catching plays his 1980's [[Gibson Flying V]] through a tuner and distortion pedal and [[Supro|Supro amplifier]] with a 2x12 cabinet. In recent shows with EODM, Catching is seen using Orange amplifiers. He also uses an Ampeg Dan Armstrong guitar when playing with [[Eagles of Death Metal]]. Catching also uses [http://www.HipStrap.com.ar HipStrap] vintage styled guitar straps. He is endorsed by and uses coiled red Bullet Cable. During recordings he also uses some of [[Jesse Hughes (musician)|Jesse Hughes]]'s [[Maton]]s.\n\nCatching released a signature fuzz wah pedal in 2015, the [http://drno-effects.com/products/roadrunner/ Roadrunner], through Dr. No Effects.\n\nWith the earthlings?, he uses his 1958 [[Fender Stratocaster]] or his 1972 double cutaway [[Gibson Les Paul]] through a tuner and a distortion Rat pedal.<!--[[Dunlop Cry Baby|Cry Baby]], [[Boss Corporation|BOSS Digital delay]], [[Phaser (effect)|Phase 90]] into a [[Silvertone (instruments)|Silvertone Twin 12]] and [[Fender Super Reverb]] amplifiers. please clarify and then insert again--><ref>[http://www.maton.com.au/interviews/dave-catching.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204131928/http://www.maton.com.au/interviews/dave-catching.html |date=December 4, 2008 }}</ref> His Les Paul is 1 of 6 ever made by Strings & Things in Memphis, Tennessee. Other guitars were bought by [[Ace Frehley]], [[Jeff Beck]], [[Pat Travers]], and Michael Woods, guitarist for the group [[America (band)|America]]. Photos have circulated of Dave's very guitar nearly being bought by [[Greg Lake]] of [[Emerson, Lake, and Palmer]] fame, but opting out at the last minute for an acoustic bass.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ladiesofthelake.com/cabinet/shop.html |title=Shopping With Greg Lake |publisher=Ladies of the Lake |accessdate=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Partial discography==\n* ''The Modifiers'' (1980's]\n* ''60 Watt Reality'' (The Ringling Sisters, 1990)\n* ''[[Volumes 1 & 2|The Desert Sessions 1 & 2]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Queens of the Stone Age (album)|Queens of the Stone Age]]'' (Queens of the Stone Age, 1998)\n*\"[[Scraps at Midnight]] ((Mark Lanegan 1998)\n* ''[[Volumes 3 & 4|The Desert Sessions 3 & 4]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Volumes 5 & 6|The Desert Sessions 5 & 6]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Rated R (Queens of the Stone Age album)|Rated R]]'' (Queens of the Stone Age, 2000)\n* ''[[Human Beans]]'' (earthlings?, 2001)\n* ''[[Deep in the Hole (album)|Deep in the Hole]]'' ([[Masters of Reality]], 2001)\n* ''[[Songs for the Deaf]]'' (Queens of the Stone Age, 2002)\n* ''[[A Drug Problem That Never Existed]]'' (Mondo Generator, 2003)\n* ''[[Volumes 9 & 10|The Desert Sessions 9 & 10]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Bubblegum (Mark Lanegan album)|Bubblegum]]'' (Mark Lanegan Band, 2004)\n* ''[[III the EP]]'' (Mondo Generator, 2004)\n*[[Cowboy Coffee and Burnt Knives]] (Hulk 2004)\n* ''[[Lullabies to Paralyze]]'' (Queens of the Stone Age, 2005)\n* ''[[I Got a Brand New Egg Layin' Machine]]'' ([[Goon Moon]], 2005)\n* ''[[Death By Sexy]]...'' (Eagles of Death Metal, 2006)\n* ''[[Powder Burns]]'' (The Twilight Singers, 2006)\n* ''[[Dead Planet]]'' (Mondo Generator, 2006)\n* ''[[Licker's Last Leg]]'' (Goon Moon, 2007)\n* [[Neptune (The Duke Spirit album)|''Neptune'']] ([[The Duke Spirit]], 2008)\n*[[Prime Motivator]] (Giraffes 2008)\n*[[Heart On]] (Eagles of Death Metal 2008)\n*[[Saturnalia]] (Gutter Twins 2008)\n* ''[[Humalien]]'' ([[earthlings?]], 2009)\n* ''[[Pine Cross Dover]]'' (Masters of Reality, 2009)\n* ''[[Blues Funeral]]'' (Mark Lanegan Band, 2012)\n* ''Tomorrowland Blues'' (Star & Dagger, 2013)\n*[[Do to the Beast]] (Afghan Whigs 2014)\n* ''Unfuckwithable'' (Mojave Lords, 2014)\n*[[ecaps]] (earthlings? 2014)\n*[[Wild Nights]] (Pins 2015)\n* ''[[The Mutants (musical collaboration)#Your Desert My Mind .282016.29|Your Desert My Mind]]'' (The Mutants, 2016)\n*[[Mudda Fudda]] (earthlings? 2016)\n* ''[[The Golden West (album)]]'' ([[Gayle Skidmore]], 2017)\n*[[Shared Hallucinations Pt.1]] (David Catching and Friends 2017)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Eagles of Death Metal}}\n{{Queens of the Stone Age}}\n{{Mondo Generator}}\n{{earthlings?}}{{Masters of Reality|state=autocollapse}} \n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Catching, David}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Queens of the Stone Age members]]\n[[Category:Survivors of terrorist attacks]]\n[[Category:November 2015 Paris attacks]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Mondo Generator members]]\n[[Category:Eagles of Death Metal members]]\n[[Category:Earthlings? members]]\n[[Category:Masters of Reality members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{one source|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Dave Catching\n| image                 = Dave Catching playing with the Eagles of Death Metal at the Commodore Ballroom July 20th 2009.jpg\n| caption            = Dave Catching performing with the [[Eagles of Death Metal]] at the Commodore Ballroom in [[Vancouver, British Columbia]]\n| image_size            = 250\n| landscape           = Yes\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = David Catching\n| alias               = Diamond Dave<br>Darlin' Dave <br> Davey Jo <br> Snohawk \n| birth_date      =  {{birth date and age|1961|6|7}}\n| origin              = [[Memphis, Tennessee]], US\n| genre               = [[Stoner rock]], [[hard rock]], [[Palm Desert Scene|desert rock]], [[garage rock revival]], [[acid rock]], [[psychedelic rock]], [[blues rock]]\n| occupation          = Musician, songwriter, producer\n| years_active        = 1982\u2013present\n| instrument          = Vocals, guitar, bass guitar, piano, keyboard, [[lap steel]], [[twelve-string guitar]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Queens of the Stone Age]], [[Eagles of Death Metal]], [[Tex & the Horseheads]], The Ringling Sisters, [[Mojave Lords]], [[earthlings?]], [[Mark Lanegan]], Gnarltones, Pink Slip, [[Mondo Generator]], [[Smith & Pyle]], [[Masters of Reality]], Star & Dagger, [[Peaches (musician)|Peaches]], [[The Mutants (musical collaboration)|The Mutants]]\n}}\n\n'''David Catching''' (born June 7, 1961) is an American musician and producer from [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], [[Tennessee]]. He is a founding member of the California [[stoner rock]] band [[earthlings?]], a touring member of [[Eagles of Death Metal]] and the co-founder of the [[Rancho De La Luna]] recording studio.\n\n[[File:Catching1.jpg|thumb|220px|alt=text|Dave Catching playing with [[Eagles of Death Metal]] live at The Glass House February 8, 2006]]\n\n==Recording career==\nCatching has played the guitar for well-known hard rock bands [[Eagles of Death Metal]], [[Queens of the Stone Age]], [[Tex and the Horseheads]], The Ringling Sisters, [[earthlings?]], [[Mondo Generator]] and the [[Masters of Reality]]. He is also a member of [[Yellow#5]], and the Gnarltones.\n\nCatching has been associated with the desert country rock band, [[Smith & Pyle]]. He contributed to the debut album of country rock duo [[Smith & Pyle]], ''It's OK to be Happy'', which was recorded at [[Rancho de la Luna]] and released in 2008. He currently resides in [[Joshua Tree, California]].\n\nCatching was on stage with Eagles of Death Metal during the [[November 2015 Paris attacks]], and escaped the [[Bataclan (theatre)|Bataclan]] with the rest of the band.\n\n==Musical equipment==\nWith the Eagles of Death Metal, Catching plays his 1980's [[Gibson Flying V]] through a tuner and distortion pedal and [[Supro|Supro amplifier]] with a 2x12 cabinet. In recent shows with EODM, Catching is seen using Orange amplifiers. He also uses an Ampeg Dan Armstrong guitar when playing with [[Eagles of Death Metal]]. Catching also uses [http://www.HipStrap.com.ar HipStrap] vintage styled guitar straps. He is endorsed by and uses coiled red Bullet Cable. During recordings he also uses some of [[Jesse Hughes (musician)|Jesse Hughes]]'s [[Maton]]s.\n\nCatching released a signature fuzz wah pedal in 2015, the [http://drno-effects.com/products/roadrunner/ Roadrunner], through Dr. No Effects.\n\nWith the earthlings?, he uses his 1958 [[Fender Stratocaster]] or his 1972 double cutaway [[Gibson Les Paul]] through a tuner and a distortion Rat pedal.<!--[[Dunlop Cry Baby|Cry Baby]], [[Boss Corporation|BOSS Digital delay]], [[Phaser (effect)|Phase 90]] into a [[Silvertone (instruments)|Silvertone Twin 12]] and [[Fender Super Reverb]] amplifiers. please clarify and then insert again--><ref>[http://www.maton.com.au/interviews/dave-catching.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204131928/http://www.maton.com.au/interviews/dave-catching.html |date=December 4, 2008 }}</ref> His Les Paul is 1 of 6 ever made by Strings & Things in Memphis, Tennessee. Other guitars were bought by [[Ace Frehley]], [[Jeff Beck]], [[Pat Travers]], and Michael Woods, guitarist for the group [[America (band)|America]]. Photos have circulated of Dave's very guitar nearly being bought by [[Greg Lake]] of [[Emerson, Lake, and Palmer]] fame, but opting out at the last minute for an acoustic bass.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ladiesofthelake.com/cabinet/shop.html |title=Shopping With Greg Lake |publisher=Ladies of the Lake |accessdate=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Partial discography==\n* ''The Modifiers'' (1980's]\n* ''60 Watt Reality'' (The Ringling Sisters, 1990)\n* ''[[Volumes 1 & 2|The Desert Sessions 1 & 2]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Queens of the Stone Age (album)|Queens of the Stone Age]]'' (Queens of the Stone Age, 1998)\n*\"[[Scraps at Midnight]] ((Mark Lanegan 1998)\n* ''[[Volumes 3 & 4|The Desert Sessions 3 & 4]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Volumes 5 & 6|The Desert Sessions 5 & 6]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Rated R (Queens of the Stone Age album)|Rated R]]'' (Queens of the Stone Age, 2000)\n* ''[[Human Beans]]'' (earthlings?, 2001)\n* ''[[Deep in the Hole (album)|Deep in the Hole]]'' ([[Masters of Reality]], 2001)\n* ''[[Songs for the Deaf]]'' (Queens of the Stone Age, 2002)\n* ''[[A Drug Problem That Never Existed]]'' (Mondo Generator, 2003)\n* ''[[Volumes 9 & 10|The Desert Sessions 9 & 10]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Bubblegum (Mark Lanegan album)|Bubblegum]]'' (Mark Lanegan Band, 2004)\n* ''[[III the EP]]'' (Mondo Generator, 2004)\n*[[Cowboy Coffee and Burnt Knives]] (Hulk 2004)\n* ''[[Lullabies to Paralyze]]'' (Queens of the Stone Age, 2005)\n* ''[[I Got a Brand New Egg Layin' Machine]]'' ([[Goon Moon]], 2005)\n* ''[[Death By Sexy]]...'' (Eagles of Death Metal, 2006)\n* ''[[Powder Burns]]'' (The Twilight Singers, 2006)\n* ''[[Dead Planet]]'' (Mondo Generator, 2006)\n* ''[[Licker's Last Leg]]'' (Goon Moon, 2007)\n* [[Neptune (The Duke Spirit album)|''Neptune'']] ([[The Duke Spirit]], 2008)\n*[[Prime Motivator]] (Giraffes 2008)\n*[[Heart On]] (Eagles of Death Metal 2008)\n*[[Saturnalia]] (Gutter Twins 2008)\n* ''[[Humalien]]'' ([[earthlings?]], 2009)\n* ''[[Pine Cross Dover]]'' (Masters of Reality, 2009)\n* ''[[Blues Funeral]]'' (Mark Lanegan Band, 2012)\n* ''Tomorrowland Blues'' (Star & Dagger, 2013)\n*[[Do to the Beast]] (Afghan Whigs 2014)\n* ''Unfuckwithable'' (Mojave Lords, 2014)\n*[[ecaps]] (earthlings? 2014)\n*[[Wild Nights]] (Pins 2015)\n* ''[[The Mutants (musical collaboration)#Your Desert My Mind .282016.29|Your Desert My Mind]]'' (The Mutants, 2016)\n*[[Mudda Fudda]] (earthlings? 2016)\n* ''[[The Golden West (album)]]'' ([[Gayle Skidmore]], 2017)\n*[[Shared Hallucinations Pt.1]] (David Catching and Friends 2017)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Eagles of Death Metal}}\n{{Queens of the Stone Age}}\n{{Mondo Generator}}\n{{earthlings?}}{{Masters of Reality|state=autocollapse}} \n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Catching, David}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Queens of the Stone Age members]]\n[[Category:Survivors of terrorist attacks]]\n[[Category:November 2015 Paris attacks]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Mondo Generator members]]\n[[Category:Eagles of Death Metal members]]\n[[Category:Earthlings? members]]\n[[Category:Masters of Reality members]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix links to titles containing #", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dave_Catching"}
{"title_page": "Jacob Collier", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Jacob Collier\n| image            = File:Jacob Collier -1180632.jpg\n| caption          = Jacob Collier at the [[Moers Festival]] 2016\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Jacob Moriarty<ref name=\"arabtimesbirthname\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.pressreader.com/kuwait/arab-times/20180129/282299615601410|title=Unique, gifted musician creating music history |first=Cezary |last=Owerkowicz |accessdate=3 November 2019|date=29 January 2018|publisher=[[Arab Times]]|via=[[PressReader]]}}</ref>\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1994|8|2}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/category/Musician-Band/JCollierMusic/about/|title=Jacob Collier|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=4 September 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[North London]], England\n| origin           = North London\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[jazz]]\n* [[funk]]\n* [[a cappella]]\n* [[R&B]]\n* [[soul music|soul]]\n* [[neo soul]]\n* [[classical music|classical]]\n* [[alternative rock]]\n* [[world music]]\n}}\n| instruments      = {{flatlist|\n* [[vocals]]\n* [[piano]]\n* [[keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n* [[double bass]]\n* [[bass guitar]]\n* [[drums]]\n* [[harmonizer]]\n* [[melodica]]\n* [[guitar]]\n* [[mandolin]]\n* [[ukulele]]\n* [[percussion]]\n* [[harpejji]]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|<!---alphabetize by surname or group name (when unclear, check article's DEFAULTSORT)-->\n* [[Sam Amidon]]\n* [[Daniel Caesar]]\n* [[Coldplay]]\n* [[Jamie Cullum]]\n* [[Dodie Clark|Dodie]]\n* [[Herbie Hancock]]\n* [[Cory Henry]]\n* [[JoJo (singer)|JoJo]]\n* [[Quincy Jones]]\n* [[Tori Kelly]]\n* [[Kimbra]]\n* [[Lianne La Havas]]\n* [[Laura Mvula]]\n* [[Metropole Orkest]]\n* [[Snarky Puppy]]\n* [[Oumou Sangare]]\n* [[Becca Stevens]]\n* [[Take 6]]\n* [[Chris Thile]]\n* [[Ty Dolla $ign]]<!---DEFAULTSORT of his article is Ty Dolla Sign-->\n* [[Steve Vai]]\n* [[Voces8]]\n* [[Pharrell Williams]]\n* [[Hans Zimmer]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* musician\n* arranger\n* composer\n* singer\n* multi-instrumentalist\n* producer\n}}\n| years_active     = 2011\u2013present\n| label            = Hajanga Records\n| website          = {{URL|jacobcollier.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Jacob Collier''' (born 2 August 1994) is an English singer, arranger, composer, producer, and multi-instrumentalist based in London, England. In 2012, his split-screen video covers of popular songs, such as [[Stevie Wonder]]'s \"[[Don't You Worry 'bout a Thing]]\", began to go viral on [[YouTube]].\n\nCollier's style fuses elements of [[jazz]], [[a cappella]], [[Groove (music)|groove]], [[Folk music|folk]], [[electronic music]], [[classical music]], [[gospel music|gospel]], [[Soul music|soul]] and [[improvisation]], and often features extreme use of [[reharmonisation]]. In 2014, Collier signed to [[Quincy Jones]]' management company and began working on his one-man, audio-visual live performance vehicle, designed and built at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://arts.mit.edu/artists/jacob-collier/#about-the-residency|title=Jacob Collier - Art At MIT|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Collier released his debut album, [[In My Room (album)|''In My Room'']], which was entirely self-recorded, arranged, performed and produced in the small back room of his family home in Finchley, north London.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jul/07/jazz-prodigy-jacob-collier-i-knew-the-sounds-i-wanted-i-just-had-to-find-out-how-to-make-them |title=Jazz prodigy Jacob Collier: 'Quincy Jones told me jazz is the classical music of pop' |last=Lewis |first=John |date=7 July 2016 |website=The Guardian |language=en-GB |access-date=6 January 2020}}</ref> In [[Grammys 2017#Arranging|2017]], Collier was awarded two [[Grammys]] for his arrangements of \"[[Meet the Flintstones|Flintstones]]\" and \"[[You and I (We Can Conquer the World)|You And I]]\", both from the album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/7686168/grammy-awards-2017-winners-list|title=Grammy Awards 2017: See the Full Winners List|website=Billboard|access-date=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Collier began working on ''Djesse'', a four-volume, 50-song album featuring more than two dozen artists and ensembles. The first album, ''[[Djesse Vol. 1]]'', was released in December 2018; and the second, ''[[Djesse Vol. 2]]'', was released in July 2019. In January 2020, Collier won two [[Grammy Awards]] for his arrangements of \"[[All Night Long (All Night)|All Night Long]]\" on ''Djesse Vol. 1'' and \"[[Moon River]]\" on ''Djesse Vol. 2''.\n\n==Life and career==\nCollier grew up in [[North London]], raised primarily by a single mother, with two younger sisters.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> He attended [[Mill Hill County High School]] in North London, and [[The Purcell School for Young Musicians]] in [[Bushey]], Hertfordshire. Collier briefly studied jazz piano at the [[Royal Academy of Music]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jazzwisemagazine.com/artists/13820-jacob-collier-the-multi-instrumentalist-youtube-sensation|accessdate= 13 June 2019|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 The Vocalist/Multi-Instrumentalist Youtube Sensation|publisher=[[Jazzwise]]}}</ref> His mother, Susan Collier, is a violinist, a conductor, and a professor at the Royal Academy of Music's Junior Academy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.susancollier.co.uk/violinist|title=SusanCollier.com|accessdate= 3 June 2016}}</ref> Collier's maternal grandfather, [[Derek Collier]], was a violinist who also taught at the Royal Academy of Music and performed with orchestras around the world. Regarding the role music plays within his family, Collier says, \"We sing [[Bach]] chorales together as family \u2013 it's just so much fun.\"<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jazzwisemagazine.com/artists/13820-jacob-collier-the-multi-instrumentalist-youtube-sensation|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 the vocalist/multi-instrumentalist YouTube sensation|website=Jazzwise Magazine|accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> Collier is partly of [[Chinese people|Chinese]] descent, through his maternal grandmother, Lila Wong.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/therecord/2016/07/11/485261328/with-in-my-room-jazz-phenom-jacob-collier-is-bringing-jubilation-back|title=With 'In My Room,' Jazz Phenom Jacob Collier Is Bringing Jubilation Back |publisher=NPR|accessdate=27 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/entertainment/jazzblog/if-you-cant-paint-in-primary-colours-no-ones-going-to-listen-to-your-songs-the-jacob-collier-interview|title=\"If you can't paint in primary colours, no one's going to listen to your songs\" \u2013 The Jacob Collier interview|first=Peter|last=Hum|date=6 July 2017|work=Ottawa Citizen|publisher=Postmedia Network Inc.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 he portrayed [[Tiny Tim (A Christmas Carol)|Tiny Tim]] in [[Arthur Allan Seidelman]]'s ''[[A Christmas Carol (2004 film)|A Christmas Carol]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.michaelvalentinestudio.com/jazz_gallery/jacob_collier/index.php|title=Jacob Collier Trio @ the PizzaExpress Jazz Club 31 May 2015|website=Michael Valentine Studio|access-date=27 December 2018}}</ref> being credited as Jacob Moriarty.<ref name=\"arabtimesbirthname\"/> At the same time, Collier was also performing as a treble singer in classical roles such as one of the three boys in Mozart's ''[[The Magic Flute]]'' and \"Miles\" in [[Benjamin Britten]]'s ''[[The Turn of the Screw (opera)|The Turn of the Screw]]'', the latter of which heavily influenced his usage and understanding of harmony.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Of Britten's harmonic language, Collier says, \"my mind was shattered outwards\".<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Collier received the [[ABRSM]] Gold Medal for the highest mark in the country for his grade eight singing result in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://joinencore.com/jacobcollier|title=Jacob Collier- Encore|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nCollier is a self-declared [[autodidact]]. He began uploading homemade, multi-instrumental content to YouTube in 2011, releasing, among others, vocal arrangements of \"[[Pure Imagination]]\", from the 1971 film ''[[Willy Wonka and the Chocolate Factory]]'', and in 2013, a multi-instrumental rendition of Stevie Wonder's \"Don't You Worry 'bout a Thing\". His activity caught the attention of [[Quincy Jones]],<ref name=\"auto1\" /> who flew Collier out to the [[Montreux Jazz Festival]] where he met with him and [[Herbie Hancock]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/interviews/meet-jacob-collier-jazz-sensation-gone-youtube-royal-albert/|title=Meet Jacob Collier: the jazz sensation that's gone from YouTube to the Royal Albert Hall|last=Hewett|first=Ivan|date=17 July 2018|work=The Telegraph|access-date=4 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u20132015: Quincy Jones, MIT, and ''Live Performance Vehicle''===\n\n{{Missing information|section|date=November 2019|Quincy Jones (and likely his impact on Jacob Collier's career)}}\n\n[[File:Jacob Collier performing at Montreux Jazz Festival.png|thumb|Jacob Collier's Live Solo Show]]\nAround this time, Ben Bloomberg, a PhD student at the [[MIT Media Lab]], reached out to Collier regarding the creation and development of musical hardware and software for live performance. Over the following months, he and Collier developed and constructed a new multimedia live experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.audioxpress.com/article/Jacob-Collier-and-Ben-Bloomberg-Turn-to-DPA-Microphones-to-Record-Live-Stage-Shows|title=Jacob Collier and Ben Bloomberg turn to DPA Microphones.|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Collier's debut live solo show was completed and began touring Europe and the US.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jazzwisemagazine.com/breaking-news/13652-quincy-jones-presents-the-future-of-music-with-jacob-collier-and-justin-kauflin|title=Quincy Jones Presents The Future of Music with Jacob Collier and Justin Kauflin at Ronnie Scott's |accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref> The performance featured a circle of musical instruments, with six simultaneous looping stations capable of simultaneous playback, backed by synced real-time 3D-captured video loops, projected onto a screen behind the instruments, courtesy of Louis Mustill and William Young of Artists and Engineers. Central to the One-Man Show was a custom-built vocal \"Harmonizer\" instrument which Collier designed and created with Bloomberg, which enabled Collier to perform multi-voice harmonies in real-time.<ref name=\"Mason\">{{cite web |last1=Mason |first1=Amelia |title=Reaching Tech's Limit, YouTube Phenom Jacob Collier Seeks A Human Touch |url=https://www.wbur.org/artery/2018/12/05/jacob-collier-youtube-phenom |website=WBUR: The Artery |publisher=Boston University |accessdate=9 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\"/> The debut performance of this show was held at [[Ronnie Scott's Jazz Club]] in London.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/jul/03/jacob-collier-review-ronnie-scotts-jazz-new-messiah|title=Jacob Collier review \u2013 jazz's new messiah|last=Lewis|first=John|date=3 July 2015|website=The Guardian|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref> A few weeks later, Collier opened for Herbie Hancock and [[Chick Corea]] with the One-Man-Show at the 2015 [[Montreux Jazz Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/jul/03/jacob-collier-review-ronnie-scotts-jazz-new-messiah|title=Jacob Collier review \u2013 jazz's new messiah|first=John|last=Lewis|date=3 July 2015|publisher=|via=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n=== 2015\u20132018: ''In My Room'', World Tour, and #IHarmU ===\nIn July 2015, [[Beats Electronics|Beats]] by [[Dr. Dre]] reached out to Collier to provide the music for 'The Game Starts Here' England [[Rugby World Cup]] campaign.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} Collier recorded an a cappella version of the well-known hymn \"Jerusalem\" for the commercial, which was aired on national television before each England match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jacobcollier.co.uk/about/|title=About- Jacob Collier|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2015, Collier began working on his debut album [[In My Room (album)|''In My Room'']], after performing with WDR Big Band in a concert in [[Cologne]], Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.wdr.de/mediathek/video/klangkoerper/bigband/video-wdr-big-band-feat-jacob-collier-100.html|title=I wish|last=wdr.de|date=2 June 2015|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.wdr.de/mediathek/video/klangkoerper/bigband/video-jacob-collier---in-my-room-100.html|title=Jacob Collier - In My Room|first=Carmen Braun / Johannes|last=Imort|date=2 June 2015|publisher=}}</ref> He arranged, recorded and produced the album entirely on his own, playing every instrument, in addition to writing eight of the eleven songs. The album was recorded and mixed in one three-month period<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VWmmWZvYEdU|title=Jacob Collier talks Quincy Jones & Debut Album \"In My Room\" w/ RobertHerrera3|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref> in the music room of his family home in [[London]], England, hence the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/kultur/musik/YouTube-Star-und-Musikgenie-Jacob-Collier,collier110.html|title=Musik - Von Jazz \u00fcber Klassik, bis Weltmusik|last=NDR|website=www.ndr.de}}</ref> It was mastered by [[Bernie Grundman]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ginalovesjazz.com/new-releases-check-2/|title=Jacob Collier - In My Room - ginalovesjazz.com - the jazz magazine by matthias kirsch|date=27 July 2016|publisher=}}</ref> and released on 1 July 2016 through the independent record label Membran Entertainment Group. Following the release, Collier embarked on a world tour with his one-man show including the 2016 Montreux Jazz Festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.montreuxjazz.com/live-concert-jacob-collier-07-july-2016|title=Live Concert - Jacob Collier - 07 July 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn anticipation of the release of [[In My Room (album)|''In My Room'']], Collier launched the \"#IHarmU\" campaign through [[Patreon]], a [[crowdfunding]] site for content creators, where $100 patrons sent him 15-second video clips of melodies, which he harmonized with multiple vocal parts with his well-known multi-screen layout, and uploaded to his social media platforms. He demonstrated this creative process in a two-hour live-stream on 31 October 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1ulJmW6IkiM|title=#IHarmU LIVE! #1 ft. Lewin Bl\u00fcmel|last=Jacob Collier|date=31 October 2017|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jazzrefound.it/2016/en/artista/jacob-collier/|title=Jacob Collier - JazzRefound 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QVIO69KZc88|title='In My Room' \u2013 Out July 1st!|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref>{{better source|date=April 2017}} Collier received more than 130 melodies and donations to the project, including from British jazz artist [[Jamie Cullum]], [[Ben Folds]], [[Herbie Hancock]], and [[Kevin Olusola]] of the a cappella group [[Pentatonix]], the latter for whom he arranged \"White Christmas\" on ''[[A Pentatonix Christmas]]'', which won a [[Contemporary A Cappella Society]] award.\n\nIn February 2016, Collier was featured on [[Snarky Puppy]]'s album, ''[[Family Dinner \u2013 Volume 2|Family Dinner - Volume 2]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/feb/11/snarky-puppy-family-dinner-vol-two-review-jazz-fusion-manchester|title=Snarky Puppy: Family Dinner Vol Two review \u2013 uninhibited, high-flying jazz-fusion|last=Fordham|first=John|date=11 February 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=27 June 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>''[[Family Dinner \u2013 Volume 2|.]]'' Then, on 22 August, Collier took part in a Quincy Jones tribute concert at the [[BBC Proms]] in the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in London, in which he performed his own orchestral arrangement of his original song, 'In The Real Early Morning', with the [[Metropole Orkest]], under the baton of [[Jules Buckley]], amongst other songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/aug/23/quincy-jones-prom-review-laura-mvula-jacob-collier-royal-albert-hall-london|title=Quincy Jones Prom review \u2013 heartfelt tribute to a great musician's extraordinary legacy|first=John|last=Fordham|date=23 August 2016|publisher=|via=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/proms-2016-a-chance-to-luxuriate-in-quincy-joness-genius--review/|title=Proms 2016: A chance to luxuriate in Quincy Jones's genius \u2013 review|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, Collier collaborated with 150 students at MIT to produce a 10 December live concert in [[Kresge Auditorium]] titled \"Imagination Off the Charts\", playing alongside orchestral arrangements of his repertoire. This residency was the subject of a documentary film,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mit.edu/2017/jacob-collier-harmonizes-with-mit-0224|title=Jacob Collier harmonizes with MIT|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LdtK_oiyJAo|title=Imagination Off the Charts: Jacob Collier comes to MIT|last=MIT Video Productions|date=8 September 2017|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> ''Imagination Off The Charts'', which won a regional [[Emmy]] in June 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jwel.mit.edu/news/mit-video-productions-wins-third-emmy-imagination-charts-jacob-collier-comes-mit|title=MIT Video Productions wins third Emmy with \"Imagination Off the Charts: Jacob Collier comes to MIT\"|date=5 June 2018|publisher=|accessdate=6 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Collier won two [[Grammy Awards]]: [[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental or A Cappella|Best Arrangement, Instrumental or A Cappella]] for the Stevie Wonder song \"[[You and I (We Can Conquer the World)|You and I]]\" and [[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental and Vocals|Best Arrangement, Instrumental and Vocals]] for a cover of \"[[Meet the Flintstones|Flintstones]]\", the theme song from the 1960s television series ''[[The Flintstones]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7ndgOS-fFkM|title=Jacob Collier GRAMMY Speech 2017|last=Quincy Jones|date=1 May 2017|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://teneightymagazine.com/2017/02/15/jacob-collier-wins-two-grammy-awards/|title=Jacob Collier Wins Two Grammy Awards \u2013 TenEighty \u2013 YouTube News, Features, and Interviews|publisher=}}</ref> One month later he made his US television debut on ''[[The Tavis Smiley Show]]'' performing a rendition of \"You And I\" with jazz-gospel a cappella group [[Take 6]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/tavissmiley/interviews/grammy-winning-performer-jacob-collier/?show=29477|title=Grammy Winning Performer Jacob Collier - Interviews - Tavis Smiley - PBS|publisher=}}</ref> In 2017, Collier also recomposed Samsung's signature ringtone, \"Over The Horizon\", for the new [[Samsung Galaxy]] S8/S8+,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.samsung.com/global/samsung-and-jacob-collier-collaborate-on-new-galaxy-smartphones-over-the-horizon|title=Samsung and Jacob Collier Collaborate on New Galaxy Smartphones' 'Over the Horizon'|publisher=}}</ref> and was co-producer on two songs from [[Becca Stevens]] album, ''Regina''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beccastevens.com/about|title=About - Becca Stevens|first=Giraffic Themes |last=www.girafficthemes.com|publisher=}}</ref> Collier also helped score [[DreamWorks Animation|DreamWorks]]\u2019 2017 film, ''[[The Boss Baby]],'' with composer [[Hans Zimmer]].<ref>{{Citation|title=The Boss Baby (2017)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3874544/fullcredits?ref_=ttco_sa_1|accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref> The following month, Collier performed with [[Hans Zimmer]] and [[Pharrell Williams]] at [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hans-zimmers-coachella-diary-fantastic-shambles-guest-column-997280|title=Hans Zimmer's Coachella Diary: \"It's Fantastic Shambles\" (Guest Column)|publisher=}}</ref> In April, Collier was also a guest on the daily weekday talk show ''[[Harry (talk show)|Harry]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://harrytv.com/episodes/april-19/|title=John Lithgow & singer Jacob Collier! - HARRY|publisher=|access-date=19 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420143726/https://harrytv.com/episodes/april-19/|archive-date=20 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JV5vzWTznFE|title=How Jacob Collier Went Viral|last=HARRY|date=19 April 2017|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> and a speaker at the annual [[TED (conference)|TED conference]] in Vancouver, Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.ted.com/tag/jacob-collier/|title=Jacob Collier - TED Blog|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nCollier toured internationally with his One-Man-Show for two and a half years (between 1 July 2015 and 18 December 2017),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.luzernerzeitung.ch/nachrichten/kultur/die-klangmesse-eines-genies;art9643,1071645|title=Die Klangmesse eines Genies|first=Luzerner Zeitung AG 6006|last=Luzern|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/entertainment/jazzblog/jazzfest-review-jacob-collier-uplifted-fans-with-his-mind-blowing-show|title=Jazzfest review: Jacob Collier uplifted fans with his mind-blowing show|date=4 July 2017|publisher=|accessdate=6 September 2018}}</ref> alongside hosting masterclasses, and performances with orchestras and big bands around the world, including the [[Metropole Orkest]]. On 9 July, he and [[Cory Henry]] performed again with the Metropole Orkest and Jules Buckley at [[North Sea Jazz Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sY8pCnKSSVg|title=Hideaway - Jacob Collier & Metropole Orkest|last=Jacob Collier|date=23 July 2017|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> In December 2017, Collier collaborated with American Pop/R&B singer [[Tori Kelly]] to record an a cappella YouTube video cover of the Christmas song \"[[Have Yourself A Merry Little Christmas]]\".<ref>{{Citation|last=Jacob Collier|title=Have Yourself A Merry Little Christmas (ft. Tori Kelly) - Jacob Collier|date=12 December 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XsVy4ImgM0o|access-date=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Collier announced that the final performance with the One-Man-Show would be held in Rome on 18 December 2017. He discussed plans for a second album, to be recorded in 2018.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nIn July 2018, Collier was one of the surprise guests at Quincy Jones' 85th birthday party celebrations, at the Montreux Jazz Club.{{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\nOn 19 July, \"Jacob Collier and Friends\" took the stage for a special concert as part of the [[BBC Proms]] at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in London. Collier performed alongside the [[Metropole Orkest]] under conductor [[Jules Buckley]], and invited [[Take 6]], [[Sam Amidon]], [[Becca Stevens]], and Maalem Gnawa musician [[Hamid El Kasri]] to be a part of the performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/e88qwh|title=Prom 7: Jacob Collier and Friends|website=BBC Music Events|accessdate=6 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018\u2013present: ''Djesse'' ===\nOn 29 October 2018, Collier announced a new four-volume, 50-song musical project, titled ''Djesse''.<ref name=\"djesse-announce\">{{Citation|last=Collier |first=Jacob |title=DJESSE Announcement!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hN0bCQjdqQM|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Mason\"/>\n\nFollowing a one-week residency at [[MIT]], ''Djesse (Vol. 1)'' was premiered live in [[Kresge Auditorium]] on 8 December 2018. The concert featured his performance with the MIT JC Orchestra (composed of MIT and [[Berklee College]] musicians), MIT Festival Jazz Ensemble, MIT Vocal Jazz Ensemble, MIT Concert Choir and Chamber Chorus, Rambax MIT ([[Music of Senegal|Senegalese drumming]] ensemble), Suzie Collier (Jacob's mother), and other special guest musicians from Boston and Los Angeles.<ref name=\"MIT2018\">{{cite web |title=Jacob Collier |url=https://arts.mit.edu/artists/jacob-collier/#events |website=Arts at MIT |publisher=MIT Center for Art, Science & Technology (CAST) |accessdate=9 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Mason\"/> Ben Bloomberg, designer of Collier's \"Harmonizer\" equipment and again a collaborator at MIT,<ref name=\"Mason\"/> was present in the audience and acknowledged by Collier. The sold-out concert, accompanied by a laser and LED display lightshow spectacular using custom-built lighting apparatus on-stage, was open to the MIT community as well as Boston aficionados.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jacob Collier at MIT: Djesse Volume 1 Album Release Celebration! |url=https://www.eventbrite.com/e/jacob-collier-at-mit-djesse-volume-1-album-release-celebration-tickets-49957730918# |website=Eventbrite |accessdate=9 April 2019 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nThe first single of the Djesse project, \"With The Love in My Heart\", was released on 2 November. Two further singles, \"Ocean Wide, Canyon Deep\" and \"All Night Long\", were released in late November. ''[[Djesse Vol. 1]]'' was released in full on 7 December.<ref name=\"aurev2018\">{{Cite web|url=https://sungenre.com/music/review-jacob-collier-djesse-vol-1/|title=Review: Jacob Collier - Djesse Vol. 1|last=Webb|first=Dan|date=1 December 2018|website=Sungenre|language=en-AU|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref> The volume features collaborations with [[Voces8]], [[Laura Mvula]], [[Hamid El Kasri]], [[Take 6]], and his mother, Suzie Collier. The [[Metropole Orkest]] featured heavily throughout the album, appearing on every track in addition to Collier's vocals and various instruments. Collier produced, arranged and orchestrated the music himself.\n\nIn January 2019, Collier began the ''Djesse'' World Tour. No longer a one-man-show, Collier is now backed by a band, including the Portuguese multi-instrumentalist Maro, bassist Robin Mullarkey, and drummer Christian Euman.<ref name=\"aurev2018\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://launch.theaureview.com/music/album-of-the-week-jacob-collier-djesse-vol-1-2018-lp/|title=Album of the Week: Jacob Collier - Djesse Vol. 1 (2018 LP)|date=5 December 2018|website=The AU Review|language=en-AU|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe first single from ''[[Djesse Vol. 2]]'', \"Make Me Cry\", was released on 12 April 2019.<ref>{{cite twitter|user=jacobcollier|number=1117091278125137920|date=13 April 2019|title=\u2018Make Me Cry\u2019 was released yesterday into the world!}}</ref> On 26 April 2019, Collier released the second single from ''Djesse (Vol. 2),'' a cover of [[The Beatles]]' song \"[[Here Comes The Sun]]\" in collaboration with [[Dodie Clark]]. The third Vol. 2 single was released on 13 June 2019, an ''[[a cappella]]'' arrangement of \"[[Moon River]]\" by [[Henry Mancini]] and [[Johnny Mercer]] with over a hundred vocal contributions from family members, mentors, friends, and other ''Djesse'' collaborators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://floodmagazine.com/62781/maestro-jacob-collier-splits-moon-river-into-a-five-thousand-part-vocal-symphony/|title=Maestro Jacob Collier Splits \"Moon River\" into a Five Thousand Part Vocal Symphony|website=FLOOD|language=en-US|access-date=29 June 2019}}</ref> The fourth and final single from ''Djesse Vol. 2'', \"It Don't Matter\" featuring vocals of American singer-songwriter [[JoJo (singer)|JoJo]] was released on 5 July 2019.\n\n''Djesse Vol. 2'' was released on 19 July 2019, featuring cover artwork designed by Astrig Akseralian and further musical collaborations with Lianne La Havas, Oumou Sangar\u00e9, Chris Thile, Sam Amidon, Steve Vai, Kathryn Tickell, Becca Stevens, & MARO.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nOn 20 November 2019, ''Djesse Vol. 1'' and ''Vol. 2'' each garnered a nomination for the [[62nd Annual Grammy Awards]], for \"All Night Long\" (feat. Take 6) and \"Moon River\" respectively.<ref name=\"62ndgrammynoms\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2019-11-20/la-et-ms-2020-grammy-nominations-winners-list-2020|title=2020 Grammy nominations complete list: See who's up for what|last=Lewis|first=Dave|date=20 November 2019|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=21 November 2019}}</ref> The nominated tracks both won their respective categories at the awards.<ref name=\"2020grammysinitialsource\"/>\n\nIn November 2019, Collier announced the first single from ''Djesse Vol. 3'', \"Time Alone With You\" in collaboration with [[Daniel Caesar]], which was released on 29 November 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Time Alone With You |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v6jWgsd52Vk |date=27 November 2019 |access-date=11 January 2020}}</ref> The video for the song premiered on YouTube on 5 December.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jacob Collier - Time Alone With You (feat. Daniel Caesar) Official Video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2qUCyW7ewPs |date=5 December 2019 |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Collier also appeared on three songs on [[Coldplay]]'s eighth studio album, [[Everyday Life (Coldplay album)|''Everyday Life'']], providing backing vocals for the tracks \"Cry, Cry, Cry\", \"Everyday Life\", and \"Church\".<ref name=\"AmericanSongwriter2019\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Jacob Collier Announces 2020 Tour Dates, Releases \"Time Alone With You\" |url=https://americansongwriter.com/jacob-collier-announces-2020-tour-dates-releases-time-alone-with-you/press-release/ |publisher=American Songwriter |date=30 November 2019 |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nCollier was scheduled to continue touring the world in 2020 starting with a new run of announced ''Djesse'' World Tour dates in Europe and North America for spring 2020.<ref name=\"AmericanSongwriter2019\" /> However, the tour was postponed due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B91uT-CAYrx/|title=Jacob Collier on Instagram: \u201c\u26fa\ufe0f\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn March 2020, Collier released the second single from ''Djesse Vol. 3'', \"In My Bones (feat. Kimbra & Tank and The Bangas)\", premiering the music video on the same day on his YouTube channel.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"7\" | Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Heatseekers Albums|US<br>Heat.]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jacob-collier/chart-history/heatseekers-albums|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 Chart History|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Independent Albums|US<br>Indie]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jacob-collier/chart-history/independent-albums|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 Chart History|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Billboard charts|US<br>Contemporary Jazz]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jacob-collier/chart-history/JCR|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 Chart History|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2 November 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Billboard charts|US<br>Jazz]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jacob-collier/chart-history/jazz-albums|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 Chart History|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Billboard charts|US<br>Classical]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jacob-collier/chart-history/classical-albums|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 Chart History|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Billboard charts|US<br>Classical Cross.]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jacob-collier/chart-history/CCF|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 Chart History|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Americana/Folk Albums|US<br>Folk Sales]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jacob-collier/chart-history/AMF|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 Chart History|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=24 October 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[In My Room (album)|In My Room]]''\n|\n* Released: 1 July 2016\n* Label: Membran\n* Formats: [[Compact disc|CD]], [[LP record|LP]], [[Music download|digital download]]\n| 10 || 50 || 1 || 3 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Djesse Vol. 1]]'' <small>(with the [[Metropole Orkest]] and [[Jules Buckley]])</small>''\n|\n* Released: 7 December 2018\n* Label: Hajanga Records, [[Geffen Records|Geffen]], [[Decca Records|Decca]]\n* Formats: CD, digital download\n| 14 || \u2014 || 1 || 6 || 6 || 6 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Djesse Vol. 2]]''\n|\n* Released: 19 July 2019\n* Label: Hajanga Records, [[Geffen Records|Geffen]], [[Decca Records|Decca]]\n* Formats: CD, digital download\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 18\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n=== Grammy Awards ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Nominated Work\n! Award\n! Result\n! Ref\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2017\n| \"[[You and I (We Can Conquer the World)|You and I]]\"\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental or A Cappella|Best Arrangement, Instrumental or A Cappella]]\n| {{Won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-grammys-2017-nominations-winners-list-20161205-story.html|title=2017 Grammy Awards: Complete list of nominees|last=Gauthier|first=Robert|date=6 December 2016|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=6 December 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| \"[[Meet the Flintstones|Flintstones]]\"\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental and Vocals|Best Arrangement, Instruments and Vocals]]\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2020\n| \"[[Moon River]]\"\n| Best Arrangement, Instrumental or A Cappella\n| {{Won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<ref name=\"2020grammysinitialsource\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/26/arts/music/grammy-winners.html |title=Grammy Winners: Who Won So Far |first=Lauren |last=Messman |date=26 January 2020 |accessdate=26 January 2020|website=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|\"[[All Night Long (All Night)|All Night Long]]\"\n| Best Arrangement, Instruments and Vocals\n| {{Won}}\n|}\n\n=== Jazz FM Awards ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Nominated Work\n! Category\n! Result\n! Ref\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2016\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Himself\n| Breakout Artist of the Year\n| {{Nom}}\n|<ref name=\"jazzfm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jazzfm.com/on-air/jazz-fm-award-winners-2016/|title=Jazz FM Award Winners 2016|accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| Digital Initiative of the Year (Sponsored by 7digital)\n| {{Won}}\n|<ref name=\"jazzfm\" />\n|-\n| 2019\n| PRS For Music Gold Award\n| {{Won}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/jacob-collier-gold-jazz-fm-awards/|title=Jazz FM Award Winners 2019|accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2020\n| The Digital Award\n| {{Nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicweek.com/media/read/charles-lloyd-philip-bailey-anderson-paak-and-celeste-lead-jazz-fm-awards-2020-nominations/079233/|title=Jazz FM Awards 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== MOBO Awards ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Nominated Work\n! Category\n! Result\n! Ref\n|-\n|2016\n| Himself\n| Best JAZZ Act\n| {{Nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voting.mobo.com/categories/jazz-act/|title=MOBO Awards Best Jazz Act|accessdate=6 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220100421/http://voting.mobo.com/categories/jazz-act/|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of songs recorded by Jacob Collier]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n{{Jacob Collier}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Collier, Jacob}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:English musicians]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English people of Chinese descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Jacob Collier\n| image            = File:Jacob Collier -1180632.jpg\n| caption          = Jacob Collier at the [[Moers Festival]] 2016\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Jacob Moriarty<ref name=\"arabtimesbirthname\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.pressreader.com/kuwait/arab-times/20180129/282299615601410|title=Unique, gifted musician creating music history |first=Cezary |last=Owerkowicz |accessdate=3 November 2019|date=29 January 2018|publisher=[[Arab Times]]|via=[[PressReader]]}}</ref>\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1994|8|2}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/category/Musician-Band/JCollierMusic/about/|title=Jacob Collier|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=4 September 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[North London]], England\n| origin           = North London\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[jazz]]\n* [[funk]]\n* [[a cappella]]\n* [[R&B]]\n* [[soul music|soul]]\n* [[neo soul]]\n* [[classical music|classical]]\n* [[alternative rock]]\n* [[world music]]\n}}\n| instruments      = {{flatlist|\n* [[vocals]]\n* [[piano]]\n* [[keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n* [[double bass]]\n* [[bass guitar]]\n* [[drums]]\n* [[harmonizer]]\n* [[melodica]]\n* [[guitar]]\n* [[mandolin]]\n* [[ukulele]]\n* [[percussion]]\n* [[harpejji]]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|<!---alphabetize by surname or group name (when unclear, check article's DEFAULTSORT)-->\n* [[Sam Amidon]]\n* [[Daniel Caesar]]\n* [[Coldplay]]\n* [[Jamie Cullum]]\n* [[Dodie Clark|Dodie]]\n* [[Herbie Hancock]]\n* [[Cory Henry]]\n* [[JoJo (singer)|JoJo]]\n* [[Quincy Jones]]\n* [[Tori Kelly]]\n* [[Kimbra]]\n* [[Lianne La Havas]]\n* [[Laura Mvula]]\n* [[Metropole Orkest]]\n* [[Snarky Puppy]]\n* [[Oumou Sangare]]\n* [[Becca Stevens]]\n* [[Take 6]]\n* [[Chris Thile]]\n* [[Ty Dolla $ign]]<!---DEFAULTSORT of his article is Ty Dolla Sign-->\n* [[Steve Vai]]\n* [[Voces8]]\n* [[Pharrell Williams]]\n* [[Hans Zimmer]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* musician\n* arranger\n* composer\n* singer\n* multi-instrumentalist\n* producer\n}}\n| years_active     = 2011\u2013present\n| label            = Hajanga Records\n| website          = {{URL|jacobcollier.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Jacob Collier''' (born 2 August 1994) is an English singer, arranger, composer, producer, and multi-instrumentalist based in London, England. In 2012, his split-screen video covers of popular songs, such as [[Stevie Wonder]]'s \"[[Don't You Worry 'bout a Thing]]\", began to go viral on [[YouTube]].\n\nCollier's style fuses elements of [[jazz]], [[a cappella]], [[Groove (music)|groove]], [[Folk music|folk]], [[electronic music]], [[classical music]], [[gospel music|gospel]], [[Soul music|soul]] and [[improvisation]], and often features extreme use of [[reharmonisation]]. In 2014, Collier signed to [[Quincy Jones]]' management company and began working on his one-man, audio-visual live performance vehicle, designed and built at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://arts.mit.edu/artists/jacob-collier/#about-the-residency|title=Jacob Collier - Art At MIT|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Collier released his debut album, [[In My Room (album)|''In My Room'']], which was entirely self-recorded, arranged, performed and produced in the small back room of his family home in Finchley, north London.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jul/07/jazz-prodigy-jacob-collier-i-knew-the-sounds-i-wanted-i-just-had-to-find-out-how-to-make-them |title=Jazz prodigy Jacob Collier: 'Quincy Jones told me jazz is the classical music of pop' |last=Lewis |first=John |date=7 July 2016 |website=The Guardian |language=en-GB |access-date=6 January 2020}}</ref> In [[Grammys 2017#Arranging|2017]], Collier was awarded two [[Grammys]] for his arrangements of \"[[Meet the Flintstones|Flintstones]]\" and \"[[You and I (We Can Conquer the World)|You And I]]\", both from the album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/7686168/grammy-awards-2017-winners-list|title=Grammy Awards 2017: See the Full Winners List|website=Billboard|access-date=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Collier began working on ''Djesse'', a four-volume, 50-song album featuring more than two dozen artists and ensembles. The first album, ''[[Djesse Vol. 1]]'', was released in December 2018; and the second, ''[[Djesse Vol. 2]]'', was released in July 2019. In January 2020, Collier won two [[Grammy Awards]] for his arrangements of \"[[All Night Long (All Night)|All Night Long]]\" on ''Djesse Vol. 1'' and \"[[Moon River]]\" on ''Djesse Vol. 2''.\n\n==Life and career==\nCollier grew up in [[North London]], raised primarily by a single mother, with two younger sisters.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> He attended [[Mill Hill County High School]] in North London, and [[The Purcell School for Young Musicians]] in [[Bushey]], Hertfordshire. Collier briefly studied jazz piano at the [[Royal Academy of Music]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jazzwisemagazine.com/artists/13820-jacob-collier-the-multi-instrumentalist-youtube-sensation|accessdate= 13 June 2019|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 The Vocalist/Multi-Instrumentalist Youtube Sensation|publisher=[[Jazzwise]]}}</ref> His mother, Susan Collier, is a violinist, a conductor, and a professor at the Royal Academy of Music's Junior Academy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.susancollier.co.uk/violinist|title=SusanCollier.com|accessdate= 3 June 2016}}</ref> Collier's maternal grandfather, [[Derek Collier]], was a violinist who also taught at the Royal Academy of Music and performed with orchestras around the world. Regarding the role music plays within his family, Collier says, \"We sing [[Bach]] chorales together as family \u2013 it's just so much fun.\"<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jazzwisemagazine.com/artists/13820-jacob-collier-the-multi-instrumentalist-youtube-sensation|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 the vocalist/multi-instrumentalist YouTube sensation|website=Jazzwise Magazine|accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> Collier is partly of [[Chinese people|Chinese]] descent, through his maternal grandmother, Lila Wong.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/therecord/2016/07/11/485261328/with-in-my-room-jazz-phenom-jacob-collier-is-bringing-jubilation-back|title=With 'In My Room,' Jazz Phenom Jacob Collier Is Bringing Jubilation Back |publisher=NPR|accessdate=27 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/entertainment/jazzblog/if-you-cant-paint-in-primary-colours-no-ones-going-to-listen-to-your-songs-the-jacob-collier-interview|title=\"If you can't paint in primary colours, no one's going to listen to your songs\" \u2013 The Jacob Collier interview|first=Peter|last=Hum|date=6 July 2017|work=Ottawa Citizen|publisher=Postmedia Network Inc.}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 he portrayed [[Tiny Tim (A Christmas Carol)|Tiny Tim]] in [[Arthur Allan Seidelman]]'s ''[[A Christmas Carol (2004 film)|A Christmas Carol]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.michaelvalentinestudio.com/jazz_gallery/jacob_collier/index.php|title=Jacob Collier Trio @ the PizzaExpress Jazz Club 31 May 2015|website=Michael Valentine Studio|access-date=27 December 2018}}</ref> being credited as Jacob Moriarty.<ref name=\"arabtimesbirthname\"/> At the same time, Collier was also performing as a treble singer in classical roles such as one of the three boys in Mozart's ''[[The Magic Flute]]'' and \"Miles\" in [[Benjamin Britten]]'s ''[[The Turn of the Screw (opera)|The Turn of the Screw]]'', the latter of which heavily influenced his usage and understanding of harmony.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Of Britten's harmonic language, Collier says, \"my mind was shattered outwards\".<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Collier received the [[ABRSM]] Gold Medal for the highest mark in the country for his grade eight singing result in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://joinencore.com/jacobcollier|title=Jacob Collier- Encore|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nCollier is a self-declared [[autodidact]]. He began uploading homemade, multi-instrumental content to YouTube in 2011, releasing, among others, vocal arrangements of \"[[Pure Imagination]]\", from the 1971 film ''[[Willy Wonka and the Chocolate Factory]]'', and in 2013, a multi-instrumental rendition of Stevie Wonder's \"Don't You Worry 'bout a Thing\". His activity caught the attention of [[Quincy Jones]],<ref name=\"auto1\" /> who flew Collier out to the [[Montreux Jazz Festival]] where he met with him and [[Herbie Hancock]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/interviews/meet-jacob-collier-jazz-sensation-gone-youtube-royal-albert/|title=Meet Jacob Collier: the jazz sensation that's gone from YouTube to the Royal Albert Hall|last=Hewett|first=Ivan|date=17 July 2018|work=The Telegraph|access-date=4 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u20132015: Quincy Jones, MIT, and ''Live Performance Vehicle''===\n\n{{Missing information|section|date=November 2019|Quincy Jones (and likely his impact on Jacob Collier's career)}}\n\n[[File:Jacob Collier performing at Montreux Jazz Festival.png|thumb|Jacob Collier's Live Solo Show]]\nAround this time, Ben Bloomberg, a PhD student at the [[MIT Media Lab]], reached out to Collier regarding the creation and development of musical hardware and software for live performance. Over the following months, he and Collier developed and constructed a new multimedia live experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.audioxpress.com/article/Jacob-Collier-and-Ben-Bloomberg-Turn-to-DPA-Microphones-to-Record-Live-Stage-Shows|title=Jacob Collier and Ben Bloomberg turn to DPA Microphones.|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Collier's debut live solo show was completed and began touring Europe and the US.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jazzwisemagazine.com/breaking-news/13652-quincy-jones-presents-the-future-of-music-with-jacob-collier-and-justin-kauflin|title=Quincy Jones Presents The Future of Music with Jacob Collier and Justin Kauflin at Ronnie Scott's |accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref> The performance featured a circle of musical instruments, with six simultaneous looping stations capable of simultaneous playback, backed by synced real-time 3D-captured video loops, projected onto a screen behind the instruments, courtesy of Louis Mustill and William Young of Artists and Engineers. Central to the One-Man Show was a custom-built vocal \"Harmonizer\" instrument which Collier designed and created with Bloomberg, which enabled Collier to perform multi-voice harmonies in real-time.<ref name=\"Mason\">{{cite web |last1=Mason |first1=Amelia |title=Reaching Tech's Limit, YouTube Phenom Jacob Collier Seeks A Human Touch |url=https://www.wbur.org/artery/2018/12/05/jacob-collier-youtube-phenom |website=WBUR: The Artery |publisher=Boston University |accessdate=9 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\"/> The debut performance of this show was held at [[Ronnie Scott's Jazz Club]] in London.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/jul/03/jacob-collier-review-ronnie-scotts-jazz-new-messiah|title=Jacob Collier review \u2013 jazz's new messiah|last=Lewis|first=John|date=3 July 2015|website=The Guardian|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref> A few weeks later, Collier opened for Herbie Hancock and [[Chick Corea]] with the One-Man-Show at the 2015 [[Montreux Jazz Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/jul/03/jacob-collier-review-ronnie-scotts-jazz-new-messiah|title=Jacob Collier review \u2013 jazz's new messiah|first=John|last=Lewis|date=3 July 2015|publisher=|via=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n=== 2015\u20132018: ''In My Room'', World Tour, and #IHarmU ===\nIn July 2015, [[Beats Electronics|Beats]] by [[Dr. Dre]] reached out to Collier to provide the music for 'The Game Starts Here' England [[Rugby World Cup]] campaign.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} Collier recorded an a cappella version of the well-known hymn \"Jerusalem\" for the commercial, which was aired on national television before each England match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jacobcollier.co.uk/about/|title=About- Jacob Collier|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2015, Collier began working on his debut album [[In My Room (album)|''In My Room'']], after performing with WDR Big Band in a concert in [[Cologne]], Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.wdr.de/mediathek/video/klangkoerper/bigband/video-wdr-big-band-feat-jacob-collier-100.html|title=I wish|last=wdr.de|date=2 June 2015|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.wdr.de/mediathek/video/klangkoerper/bigband/video-jacob-collier---in-my-room-100.html|title=Jacob Collier - In My Room|first=Carmen Braun / Johannes|last=Imort|date=2 June 2015|publisher=}}</ref> He arranged, recorded and produced the album entirely on his own, playing every instrument, in addition to writing eight of the eleven songs. The album was recorded and mixed in one three-month period<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VWmmWZvYEdU|title=Jacob Collier talks Quincy Jones & Debut Album \"In My Room\" w/ RobertHerrera3|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref> in the music room of his family home in [[London]], England, hence the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/kultur/musik/YouTube-Star-und-Musikgenie-Jacob-Collier,collier110.html|title=Musik - Von Jazz \u00fcber Klassik, bis Weltmusik|last=NDR|website=www.ndr.de}}</ref> It was mastered by [[Bernie Grundman]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ginalovesjazz.com/new-releases-check-2/|title=Jacob Collier - In My Room - ginalovesjazz.com - the jazz magazine by matthias kirsch|date=27 July 2016|publisher=}}</ref> and released on 1 July 2016 through the independent record label Membran Entertainment Group. Following the release, Collier embarked on a world tour with his one-man show including the 2016 Montreux Jazz Festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.montreuxjazz.com/live-concert-jacob-collier-07-july-2016|title=Live Concert - Jacob Collier - 07 July 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn anticipation of the release of [[In My Room (album)|''In My Room'']], Collier launched the \"#IHarmU\" campaign through [[Patreon]], a [[crowdfunding]] site for content creators, where $100 patrons sent him 15-second video clips of melodies, which he harmonized with multiple vocal parts with his well-known multi-screen layout, and uploaded to his social media platforms. He demonstrated this creative process in a two-hour live-stream on 31 October 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1ulJmW6IkiM|title=#IHarmU LIVE! #1 ft. Lewin Bl\u00fcmel|last=Jacob Collier|date=31 October 2017|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jazzrefound.it/2016/en/artista/jacob-collier/|title=Jacob Collier - JazzRefound 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QVIO69KZc88|title='In My Room' \u2013 Out July 1st!|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref>{{better source|date=April 2017}} Collier received more than 130 melodies and donations to the project, including from British jazz artist [[Jamie Cullum]], [[Ben Folds]], [[Herbie Hancock]], and [[Kevin Olusola]] of the a cappella group [[Pentatonix]], the latter for whom he arranged \"White Christmas\" on ''[[A Pentatonix Christmas]]'', which won a [[Contemporary A Cappella Society]] award.\n\nIn February 2016, Collier was featured on [[Snarky Puppy]]'s album, ''[[Family Dinner \u2013 Volume 2|Family Dinner - Volume 2]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/feb/11/snarky-puppy-family-dinner-vol-two-review-jazz-fusion-manchester|title=Snarky Puppy: Family Dinner Vol Two review \u2013 uninhibited, high-flying jazz-fusion|last=Fordham|first=John|date=11 February 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=27 June 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>''[[Family Dinner \u2013 Volume 2|.]]'' Then, on 22 August, Collier took part in a Quincy Jones tribute concert at the [[BBC Proms]] in the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in London, in which he performed his own orchestral arrangement of his original song, 'In The Real Early Morning', with the [[Metropole Orkest]], under the baton of [[Jules Buckley]], amongst other songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/aug/23/quincy-jones-prom-review-laura-mvula-jacob-collier-royal-albert-hall-london|title=Quincy Jones Prom review \u2013 heartfelt tribute to a great musician's extraordinary legacy|first=John|last=Fordham|date=23 August 2016|publisher=|via=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/proms-2016-a-chance-to-luxuriate-in-quincy-joness-genius--review/|title=Proms 2016: A chance to luxuriate in Quincy Jones's genius \u2013 review|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, Collier collaborated with 150 students at MIT to produce a 10 December live concert in [[Kresge Auditorium]] titled \"Imagination Off the Charts\", playing alongside orchestral arrangements of his repertoire. This residency was the subject of a documentary film,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mit.edu/2017/jacob-collier-harmonizes-with-mit-0224|title=Jacob Collier harmonizes with MIT|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LdtK_oiyJAo|title=Imagination Off the Charts: Jacob Collier comes to MIT|last=MIT Video Productions|date=8 September 2017|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> ''Imagination Off The Charts'', which won a regional [[Emmy]] in June 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jwel.mit.edu/news/mit-video-productions-wins-third-emmy-imagination-charts-jacob-collier-comes-mit|title=MIT Video Productions wins third Emmy with \"Imagination Off the Charts: Jacob Collier comes to MIT\"|date=5 June 2018|publisher=|accessdate=6 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Collier won two [[Grammy Awards]]: [[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental or A Cappella|Best Arrangement, Instrumental or A Cappella]] for the Stevie Wonder song \"[[You and I (We Can Conquer the World)|You and I]]\" and [[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental and Vocals|Best Arrangement, Instrumental and Vocals]] for a cover of \"[[Meet the Flintstones|Flintstones]]\", the theme song from the 1960s television series ''[[The Flintstones]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7ndgOS-fFkM|title=Jacob Collier GRAMMY Speech 2017|last=Quincy Jones|date=1 May 2017|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://teneightymagazine.com/2017/02/15/jacob-collier-wins-two-grammy-awards/|title=Jacob Collier Wins Two Grammy Awards \u2013 TenEighty \u2013 YouTube News, Features, and Interviews|publisher=}}</ref> One month later he made his US television debut on ''[[The Tavis Smiley Show]]'' performing a rendition of \"You And I\" with jazz-gospel a cappella group [[Take 6]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/tavissmiley/interviews/grammy-winning-performer-jacob-collier/?show=29477|title=Grammy Winning Performer Jacob Collier - Interviews - Tavis Smiley - PBS|publisher=}}</ref> In 2017, Collier also recomposed Samsung's signature ringtone, \"Over The Horizon\", for the new [[Samsung Galaxy]] S8/S8+,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.samsung.com/global/samsung-and-jacob-collier-collaborate-on-new-galaxy-smartphones-over-the-horizon|title=Samsung and Jacob Collier Collaborate on New Galaxy Smartphones' 'Over the Horizon'|publisher=}}</ref> and was co-producer on two songs from [[Becca Stevens]] album, ''Regina''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beccastevens.com/about|title=About - Becca Stevens|first=Giraffic Themes |last=www.girafficthemes.com|publisher=}}</ref> Collier also helped score [[DreamWorks Animation|DreamWorks]]\u2019 2017 film, ''[[The Boss Baby]],'' with composer [[Hans Zimmer]].<ref>{{Citation|title=The Boss Baby (2017)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3874544/fullcredits?ref_=ttco_sa_1|accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref> The following month, Collier performed with [[Hans Zimmer]] and [[Pharrell Williams]] at [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hans-zimmers-coachella-diary-fantastic-shambles-guest-column-997280|title=Hans Zimmer's Coachella Diary: \"It's Fantastic Shambles\" (Guest Column)|publisher=}}</ref> In April, Collier was also a guest on the daily weekday talk show ''[[Harry (talk show)|Harry]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://harrytv.com/episodes/april-19/|title=John Lithgow & singer Jacob Collier! - HARRY|publisher=|access-date=19 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420143726/https://harrytv.com/episodes/april-19/|archive-date=20 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JV5vzWTznFE|title=How Jacob Collier Went Viral|last=HARRY|date=19 April 2017|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> and a speaker at the annual [[TED (conference)|TED conference]] in Vancouver, Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.ted.com/tag/jacob-collier/|title=Jacob Collier - TED Blog|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nCollier toured internationally with his One-Man-Show for two and a half years (between 1 July 2015 and 18 December 2017),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.luzernerzeitung.ch/nachrichten/kultur/die-klangmesse-eines-genies;art9643,1071645|title=Die Klangmesse eines Genies|first=Luzerner Zeitung AG 6006|last=Luzern|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/entertainment/jazzblog/jazzfest-review-jacob-collier-uplifted-fans-with-his-mind-blowing-show|title=Jazzfest review: Jacob Collier uplifted fans with his mind-blowing show|date=4 July 2017|publisher=|accessdate=6 September 2018}}</ref> alongside hosting masterclasses, and performances with orchestras and big bands around the world, including the [[Metropole Orkest]]. On 9 July, he and [[Cory Henry]] performed again with the Metropole Orkest and Jules Buckley at [[North Sea Jazz Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sY8pCnKSSVg|title=Hideaway - Jacob Collier & Metropole Orkest|last=Jacob Collier|date=23 July 2017|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> In December 2017, Collier collaborated with American Pop/R&B singer [[Tori Kelly]] to record an a cappella YouTube video cover of the Christmas song \"[[Have Yourself A Merry Little Christmas]]\".<ref>{{Citation|last=Jacob Collier|title=Have Yourself A Merry Little Christmas (ft. Tori Kelly) - Jacob Collier|date=12 December 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XsVy4ImgM0o|access-date=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Collier announced that the final performance with the One-Man-Show would be held in Rome on 18 December 2017. He discussed plans for a second album, to be recorded in 2018.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\nIn July 2018, Collier was one of the surprise guests at Quincy Jones' 85th birthday party celebrations, at the Montreux Jazz Club.{{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\nOn 19 July, \"Jacob Collier and Friends\" took the stage for a special concert as part of the [[BBC Proms]] at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in London. Collier performed alongside the [[Metropole Orkest]] under conductor [[Jules Buckley]], and invited [[Take 6]], [[Sam Amidon]], [[Becca Stevens]], and Maalem Gnawa musician [[Hamid El Kasri]] to be a part of the performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/e88qwh|title=Prom 7: Jacob Collier and Friends|website=BBC Music Events|accessdate=6 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018\u2013present: ''Djesse'' ===\nOn 29 October 2018, Collier announced a new four-volume, 50-song musical project, titled ''Djesse''.<ref name=\"djesse-announce\">{{Citation|last=Collier |first=Jacob |title=DJESSE Announcement!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hN0bCQjdqQM|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Mason\"/>\n\nFollowing a one-week residency at [[MIT]], ''Djesse (Vol. 1)'' was premiered live in [[Kresge Auditorium]] on 8 December 2018. The concert featured his performance with the MIT JC Orchestra (composed of MIT and [[Berklee College]] musicians), MIT Festival Jazz Ensemble, MIT Vocal Jazz Ensemble, MIT Concert Choir and Chamber Chorus, Rambax MIT ([[Music of Senegal|Senegalese drumming]] ensemble), Suzie Collier (Jacob's mother), and other special guest musicians from Boston and Los Angeles.<ref name=\"MIT2018\">{{cite web |title=Jacob Collier |url=https://arts.mit.edu/artists/jacob-collier/#events |website=Arts at MIT |publisher=MIT Center for Art, Science & Technology (CAST) |accessdate=9 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Mason\"/> Ben Bloomberg, designer of Collier's \"Harmonizer\" equipment and again a collaborator at MIT,<ref name=\"Mason\"/> was present in the audience and acknowledged by Collier. The sold-out concert, accompanied by a laser and LED display lightshow spectacular using custom-built lighting apparatus on-stage, was open to the MIT community as well as Boston aficionados.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jacob Collier at MIT: Djesse Volume 1 Album Release Celebration! |url=https://www.eventbrite.com/e/jacob-collier-at-mit-djesse-volume-1-album-release-celebration-tickets-49957730918# |website=Eventbrite |accessdate=9 April 2019 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nThe first single of the Djesse project, \"With The Love in My Heart\", was released on 2 November. Two further singles, \"Ocean Wide, Canyon Deep\" and \"All Night Long\", were released in late November. ''[[Djesse Vol. 1]]'' was released in full on 7 December.<ref name=\"aurev2018\">{{Cite web|url=https://sungenre.com/music/review-jacob-collier-djesse-vol-1/|title=Review: Jacob Collier - Djesse Vol. 1|last=Webb|first=Dan|date=1 December 2018|website=Sungenre|language=en-AU|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref> The volume features collaborations with [[Voces8]], [[Laura Mvula]], [[Hamid El Kasri]], [[Take 6]], and his mother, Suzie Collier. The [[Metropole Orkest]] featured heavily throughout the album, appearing on every track in addition to Collier's vocals and various instruments. Collier produced, arranged and orchestrated the music himself.\n\nIn January 2019, Collier began the ''Djesse'' World Tour. No longer a one-man-show, Collier is now backed by a band, including the Portuguese multi-instrumentalist Maro, bassist Robin Mullarkey, and drummer Christian Euman.<ref name=\"aurev2018\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://launch.theaureview.com/music/album-of-the-week-jacob-collier-djesse-vol-1-2018-lp/|title=Album of the Week: Jacob Collier - Djesse Vol. 1 (2018 LP)|date=5 December 2018|website=The AU Review|language=en-AU|access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe first single from ''[[Djesse Vol. 2]]'', \"Make Me Cry\", was released on 12 April 2019.<ref>{{cite twitter|user=jacobcollier|number=1117091278125137920|date=13 April 2019|title=\u2018Make Me Cry\u2019 was released yesterday into the world!}}</ref> On 26 April 2019, Collier released the second single from ''Djesse (Vol. 2),'' a cover of [[The Beatles]]' song \"[[Here Comes The Sun]]\" in collaboration with [[Dodie Clark]]. The third Vol. 2 single was released on 13 June 2019, an ''[[a cappella]]'' arrangement of \"[[Moon River]]\" by [[Henry Mancini]] and [[Johnny Mercer]] with over a hundred vocal contributions from family members, mentors, friends, and other ''Djesse'' collaborators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://floodmagazine.com/62781/maestro-jacob-collier-splits-moon-river-into-a-five-thousand-part-vocal-symphony/|title=Maestro Jacob Collier Splits \"Moon River\" into a Five Thousand Part Vocal Symphony|website=FLOOD|language=en-US|access-date=29 June 2019}}</ref> The fourth and final single from ''Djesse Vol. 2'', \"It Don't Matter\" featuring vocals of American singer-songwriter [[JoJo (singer)|JoJo]] was released on 5 July 2019.\n\n''Djesse Vol. 2'' was released on 19 July 2019, featuring cover artwork designed by Astrig Akseralian and further musical collaborations with Lianne La Havas, Oumou Sangar\u00e9, Chris Thile, Sam Amidon, Steve Vai, Kathryn Tickell, Becca Stevens, & MARO.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nOn 20 November 2019, ''Djesse Vol. 1'' and ''Vol. 2'' each garnered a nomination for the [[62nd Annual Grammy Awards]], for \"All Night Long\" (feat. Take 6) and \"Moon River\" respectively.<ref name=\"62ndgrammynoms\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2019-11-20/la-et-ms-2020-grammy-nominations-winners-list-2020|title=2020 Grammy nominations complete list: See who's up for what|last=Lewis|first=Dave|date=20 November 2019|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=21 November 2019}}</ref> The nominated tracks both won their respective categories at the awards.<ref name=\"2020grammysinitialsource\"/>\n\nIn November 2019, Collier announced the first single from ''Djesse Vol. 3'', \"Time Alone With You\" in collaboration with [[Daniel Caesar]], which was released on 29 November 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Time Alone With You |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v6jWgsd52Vk |date=27 November 2019 |access-date=11 January 2020}}</ref> The video for the song premiered on YouTube on 5 December.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jacob Collier - Time Alone With You (feat. Daniel Caesar) Official Video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2qUCyW7ewPs |date=5 December 2019 |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Collier also appeared on three songs on [[Coldplay]]'s eighth studio album, [[Everyday Life (Coldplay album)|''Everyday Life'']], providing backing vocals for the tracks \"Cry, Cry, Cry\", \"Everyday Life\", and \"Church\".<ref name=\"AmericanSongwriter2019\">{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Jacob Collier Announces 2020 Tour Dates, Releases \"Time Alone With You\" |url=https://americansongwriter.com/jacob-collier-announces-2020-tour-dates-releases-time-alone-with-you/press-release/ |publisher=American Songwriter |date=30 November 2019 |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nCollier was scheduled to continue touring the world in 2020 starting with a new run of announced ''Djesse'' World Tour dates in Europe and North America for spring 2020.<ref name=\"AmericanSongwriter2019\" /> However, the tour was postponed due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B91uT-CAYrx/|title=Jacob Collier on Instagram: \u201c\u26fa\ufe0f\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn March of 2020, Collier released the second single from ''Djesse Vol. 3'', \"In My Bones (feat. Kimbra & Tank and The Bangas)\", premiering the music video on the same day on his YouTube channel.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"7\" | Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Heatseekers Albums|US<br>Heat.]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jacob-collier/chart-history/heatseekers-albums|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 Chart History|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Independent Albums|US<br>Indie]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jacob-collier/chart-history/independent-albums|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 Chart History|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Billboard charts|US<br>Contemporary Jazz]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jacob-collier/chart-history/JCR|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 Chart History|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2 November 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Billboard charts|US<br>Jazz]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jacob-collier/chart-history/jazz-albums|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 Chart History|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Billboard charts|US<br>Classical]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jacob-collier/chart-history/classical-albums|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 Chart History|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Billboard charts|US<br>Classical Cross.]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jacob-collier/chart-history/CCF|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 Chart History|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Americana/Folk Albums|US<br>Folk Sales]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jacob-collier/chart-history/AMF|title=Jacob Collier \u2013 Chart History|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=24 October 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[In My Room (album)|In My Room]]''\n|\n* Released: 1 July 2016\n* Label: Membran\n* Formats: [[Compact disc|CD]], [[LP record|LP]], [[Music download|digital download]]\n| 10 || 50 || 1 || 3 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Djesse Vol. 1]]'' <small>(with the [[Metropole Orkest]] and [[Jules Buckley]])</small>''\n|\n* Released: 7 December 2018\n* Label: Hajanga Records, [[Geffen Records|Geffen]], [[Decca Records|Decca]]\n* Formats: CD, digital download\n| 14 || \u2014 || 1 || 6 || 6 || 6 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Djesse Vol. 2]]''\n|\n* Released: 19 July 2019\n* Label: Hajanga Records, [[Geffen Records|Geffen]], [[Decca Records|Decca]]\n* Formats: CD, digital download\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 18\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n=== Grammy Awards ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Nominated Work\n! Award\n! Result\n! Ref\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2017\n| \"[[You and I (We Can Conquer the World)|You and I]]\"\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental or A Cappella|Best Arrangement, Instrumental or A Cappella]]\n| {{Won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-grammys-2017-nominations-winners-list-20161205-story.html|title=2017 Grammy Awards: Complete list of nominees|last=Gauthier|first=Robert|date=6 December 2016|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=6 December 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| \"[[Meet the Flintstones|Flintstones]]\"\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental and Vocals|Best Arrangement, Instruments and Vocals]]\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2020\n| \"[[Moon River]]\"\n| Best Arrangement, Instrumental or A Cappella\n| {{Won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<ref name=\"2020grammysinitialsource\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/26/arts/music/grammy-winners.html |title=Grammy Winners: Who Won So Far |first=Lauren |last=Messman |date